{"title_page": "Rabi Lamichhane", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2019}}\n{{short description|Nepalese journalist}}\n{{Infobox person|\n| name               = Ram Babu gautam\n| image              = \n| birth_name         = Ram Babu Gautam\n| birth_place        = Ramechhap Nepal\n| birth_date         = B.s. 2046/1/17\nA.D.1989/04/29\n| nationality        = Nepalese\n| occupation         = Driving\n| years_active       = 2010\u2013present\n| known_for          = Dubai driving\n| spouse             = \n}}\n'''Rabi Lamichhane''' (Nepali: \u0930\u092c\u093f \u0932\u093e\u092e\u093f\u091b\u093e\u0928\u0947 ) is a  [[Nepal]]ese television presenter who set the world record for hosting the longest-ever television talk show broadcast in April, 2013.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.biofamous.com/rabi-lamichhane-biography|title=Rabi Lamichhane Biography|publisher=BioFamous}}</ref> He hosts a popular television show, ''Sidha Kura Janta Sangha'', which \"addresses the root causes of different problems inside the country\". He is best known for his \"detective-style\" journalism and raising direct questions to Nepal's bureaucracy regarding the problems of their offices in various sectors.He also has the huge craze among nepali citizen for doing the work for the welfare of people.\n\n==Career==\nRabi Lamichhane stayed on the air for more than 62 hours during a live broadcast by News24 Television. To set the world record for the longest talk show, he interviewed politicians, journalists and celebrities on the theme \"[[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]] was born in Nepal\", and took phone calls from viewers. The previous record was set by two [[Ukrainians|Ukrainian]] presenters who stayed on the air for 52 hours in 2011.<ref name=bbc>{{cite web|title=Nepali hosts longest-ever talk show|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-22140317|publisher=BBC News|date=13 April 2013|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC Australia\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-04-14/nepalese-presenter-sets-record-for-longest-talk-show/4627964|title=Nepalese presenter sets record for longest talk show - ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation)|publisher=ABC|date=14 April 2013|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nBefore moving to the U.S., he hosted ''Ma Rastrako Sewak''. He also hosted a show on [[Nepal Television]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2013-04-14/lamichhane-sets-talk-show-world-record.html|title=Lamichhane sets talk show world record|website=Ekantipur.com|publisher=[[The Kathmandu Post]]|date=14 April 2013|access-date=26 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe wrote the lyrics for [[Nabin K Bhattarai]]'s song \"Timilai Man Paraunchhu\"<ref>{{Citation|title=Timilai Mann parauchu by Nabin k. Bhattarai ft. Rabi Lamichane (OFFICIAL MUSIC VIDEO)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o2Jt1QOyOyI|language=en|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> and the song \"Timro Aagamanle feri\" sung by [[Ram Krishna Dhakal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=//www.youtube.com/watch?v=56Dw3mobNug|title=Timro aagamanle By Ram Krishna Dhakal|work=Music Nepal|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=28 August 2013|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nCurrently, he hosts ''Sidha Kura Janta Sanga'' (Translation: Direct Talk With The People) in News 24 television.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sidhakurajanatasanga.com/|title=Sidha Kura Janata Sanga \u2013 Your verdict matters!|website=sidhakurajanatasanga.com|accessdate=20 August 2017}}</ref> In 2019, it reached its 400th episode.\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe used to be the manager and supervisor of a [[Subway (restaurant)|Subway]] chain in Baltimore, Maryland, where he resided before moving to Nepal.<ref name=independent>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/nepalese-man-sets-record-for-longest-broadcast-with-62-hour-television-marathon-8572509.html|author=Richard Hall|title=Nepalese man sets record for longest broadcast with 62-hour television marathon|work=[[The Independent]]|date=14 April 2013|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref>He was born on September 14, 1974, at Bhaktapur, Nepal.\n<ref>https://www.worldtop2.com/rabi-lamichhane-biography-age-wife-education-home-family/</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\nOn 15 August 2019, Police arrested Lamichhane in his News 24 office in connection to the death of journalist Shalikram Pudasaini, which appeared to be a suicide. Video footage recorded by Pudasaini \u2014 which was made public by an online news portal \u2014 accuses Lamichhane, along with two others for his death. According to Chitwan District Police Office, they were remanded to custody, with effect from 16 August.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/shalik-ram-pudasaini-death-mysterytv-host-rabi-lamichhane-among-three-arrested/|title=Pudasaini death mystery: TV host Lamichhane among three arrested|date=2019-08-16|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref>\n\nLamichhane\u2019s fans and journalists picketed the police office. Lamichhane\u2019s supporters demonstrated outside the court and police office throughout the day, demanding his unconditional release. People from as far as Pokhara and Butwal came to participate in the demonstration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/five-day-custody-for-rabi-lamichhane-2-others/|title=Five-day custody for Rabi Lamichhane, 2 others|date=2019-08-17|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref>\n\nHe was released from custody with Rs.5,00,000 bail on 26 August. On 27 August, amid the mass of his supporters stated that he would pull up his acts against corruption in the country.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ehulaki.com/story/16813/2019/8/27/narayani-kinama-ravi|author=Keshab Niroula|title=In the banks of Narayani River, Rabi says \"I will stand much harsh against the corrupts|work=[[eHulaki]]|date=27 August 2019|accessdate=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* Sangita Panta Thapa\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lamichhane, Rabi}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Nepalese journalists]]\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2019}}\n{{short description|Nepalese journalist}}\n{{Infobox person|\n| name               = \n| image              = Rabi Lamichhane.jpg\n| birth_name         = Rabi Lamichhane\n| birth_place        = [[Kathmandu]], [[Nepal]]\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1974|9|14}}\n| nationality        = *[[Nepal]]ese (By Paternal Nationality 14 Sep. 1974 to 2007 and by re-announcement of citizenship 2017 to present)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dcnepalonline.com/featured/rabi-lamichhane-speaks-about-his-us-passport|title=Rabi Lamichhane speaks about his US Passport and current nationality.}}</ref> \n*[[Americans|American]] (2007 to 4 October 2017)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.977mag.net/presenter-rabi-lamichhane-to-hold-american-citizenship/|title=Rabi Lamichhane Holds American Citizenship Which Has Created Chaos Among His Fans}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://xnepali.net/rabi-lamichhane-to-be-arrested-deported/|title=Rabi Lamichhane to be arrested, deported for being an American citizen to host Nepalese television.}}</ref>\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Broadcast Journalist|Show host|Lyricist}}\n| years_active       = 2013\u2013present\n| known_for          = hosting the longest-ever television talk show and Sidha Kura Janta Sanga<ref>[http://sidhakurajanatasanga.com/] {{dead link|date=October 2019}}</ref>\n| spouse             = \n* Isha Lamichhane (m. ? - 2019)<ref>https://xnepali.net/rabi-had-affair-with-a-mysterious-2008-us-return-woman-says-his-ex-wife-isha-lamichhane/</ref>\n*[[Nikita Poudel]] (m. 2019) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/57786/|title=Rabi Lamichhane and Nikita Poudel get married|last=Republica|website=My City|language=en|access-date=2019-01-22}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Rabi Lamichhane''' (Nepali: \u0930\u092c\u093f \u0932\u093e\u092e\u093f\u091b\u093e\u0928\u0947 ) is a  [[Nepal]]ese television presenter who set the world record for hosting the longest-ever television talk show broadcast in April, 2013.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.biofamous.com/rabi-lamichhane-biography|title=Rabi Lamichhane Biography|publisher=BioFamous}}</ref> He hosts a popular television show, ''Sidha Kura Janta Sangha'', which \"addresses the root causes of different problems inside the country\". He is best known for his \"detective-style\" journalism and raising direct questions to Nepal's bureaucracy regarding the problems of their offices in various sectors.He also has the huge craze among nepali citizen for doing the work for the welfare of people.\n\n==Career==\nRabi Lamichhane stayed on the air for more than 62 hours during a live broadcast by News24 Television. To set the world record for the longest talk show, he interviewed politicians, journalists and celebrities on the theme \"[[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]] was born in Nepal\", and took phone calls from viewers. The previous record was set by two [[Ukrainians|Ukrainian]] presenters who stayed on the air for 52 hours in 2011.<ref name=bbc>{{cite web|title=Nepali hosts longest-ever talk show|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-22140317|publisher=BBC News|date=13 April 2013|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC Australia\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-04-14/nepalese-presenter-sets-record-for-longest-talk-show/4627964|title=Nepalese presenter sets record for longest talk show - ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation)|publisher=ABC|date=14 April 2013|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nBefore moving to the U.S., he hosted ''Ma Rastrako Sewak''. He also hosted a show on [[Nepal Television]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2013-04-14/lamichhane-sets-talk-show-world-record.html|title=Lamichhane sets talk show world record|website=Ekantipur.com|publisher=[[The Kathmandu Post]]|date=14 April 2013|access-date=26 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe wrote the lyrics for [[Nabin K Bhattarai]]'s song \"Timilai Man Paraunchhu\"<ref>{{Citation|title=Timilai Mann parauchu by Nabin k. Bhattarai ft. Rabi Lamichane (OFFICIAL MUSIC VIDEO)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o2Jt1QOyOyI|language=en|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> and the song \"Timro Aagamanle feri\" sung by [[Ram Krishna Dhakal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=//www.youtube.com/watch?v=56Dw3mobNug|title=Timro aagamanle By Ram Krishna Dhakal|work=Music Nepal|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=28 August 2013|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nCurrently, he hosts ''Sidha Kura Janta Sanga'' (Translation: Direct Talk With The People) in News 24 television.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sidhakurajanatasanga.com/|title=Sidha Kura Janata Sanga \u2013 Your verdict matters!|website=sidhakurajanatasanga.com|accessdate=20 August 2017}}</ref> In 2019, it reached its 400th episode.\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe used to be the manager and supervisor of a [[Subway (restaurant)|Subway]] chain in Baltimore, Maryland, where he resided before moving to Nepal.<ref name=independent>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/nepalese-man-sets-record-for-longest-broadcast-with-62-hour-television-marathon-8572509.html|author=Richard Hall|title=Nepalese man sets record for longest broadcast with 62-hour television marathon|work=[[The Independent]]|date=14 April 2013|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref>He was born on September 14, 1974, at Bhaktapur, Nepal.\n<ref>https://www.worldtop2.com/rabi-lamichhane-biography-age-wife-education-home-family/</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\nOn 15 August 2019, Police arrested Lamichhane in his News 24 office in connection to the death of journalist Shalikram Pudasaini, which appeared to be a suicide. Video footage recorded by Pudasaini \u2014 which was made public by an online news portal \u2014 accuses Lamichhane, along with two others for his death. According to Chitwan District Police Office, they were remanded to custody, with effect from 16 August.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/shalik-ram-pudasaini-death-mysterytv-host-rabi-lamichhane-among-three-arrested/|title=Pudasaini death mystery: TV host Lamichhane among three arrested|date=2019-08-16|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref>\n\nLamichhane\u2019s fans and journalists picketed the police office. Lamichhane\u2019s supporters demonstrated outside the court and police office throughout the day, demanding his unconditional release. People from as far as Pokhara and Butwal came to participate in the demonstration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/five-day-custody-for-rabi-lamichhane-2-others/|title=Five-day custody for Rabi Lamichhane, 2 others|date=2019-08-17|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref>\n\nHe was released from custody with Rs.5,00,000 bail on 26 August. On 27 August, amid the mass of his supporters stated that he would pull up his acts against corruption in the country.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ehulaki.com/story/16813/2019/8/27/narayani-kinama-ravi|author=Keshab Niroula|title=In the banks of Narayani River, Rabi says \"I will stand much harsh against the corrupts|work=[[eHulaki]]|date=27 August 2019|accessdate=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* Sangita Panta Thapa\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lamichhane, Rabi}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Nepalese journalists]]\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n", "name_user": "Rbg691", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rabi_Lamichhane"}
{"title_page": "Interleukin 6", "text_new": "{{Infobox gene}}\n'''Interleukin 6''' ('''IL-6''') is an [[interleukin]] that acts as both a pro-inflammatory [[cytokine]] and an anti-inflammatory [[myokine]]. In humans, it is encoded by the ''IL6'' [[gene]].<ref name=\"pmid3294161\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Ferguson-Smith AC, Chen YF, Newman MS, May LT, Sehgal PB, Ruddle FH | title = Regional localization of the interferon-beta 2/B-cell stimulatory factor 2/hepatocyte stimulating factor gene to human chromosome 7p15-p21 | journal = Genomics | volume = 2 | issue = 3 | pages = 203\u20138 | date = April 1988 | pmid = 3294161 | doi = 10.1016/0888-7543(88)90003-1 }}</ref>\n\nIn addition, [[osteoblast]]s secrete IL-6 to stimulate [[osteoclast]] formation.  [[Smooth muscle cell]]s in the [[tunica media]] of many blood vessels also produce IL-6 as a pro-inflammatory [[cytokine]].  IL-6's role as an anti-inflammatory myokine is mediated through its inhibitory effects on [[TNF-alpha]] and [[IL1A|IL-1]], and activation of [[Interleukin 1 receptor antagonist|IL-1ra]] and [[Interleukin 10|IL-10]].\n\nThere is some early evidence that IL-6 can be used as an [[inflammatory markers|inflammatory marker]] for severe [[COVID-19]] infection with poor prognosis, in the context of the wider [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Raised troponin and interleukin-6 levels are associated with a poor prognosis in COVID-19 | url = https://cardiacrhythmnews.com/raised-troponin-and-interleukin-6-levels-are-associated-with-a-poor-prognosis-in-covid-19/ | date = 2 April 2020 | work = Cardiac Rhythm News }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Gong J, Dong H, Xia SQ, Huang YZ, Wang D, Zhao Y, Liu W, Tu S, Zhang M, Wang Q, Lu F | display-authors = 6 | title = Correlation Analysis Between Disease Severity and Inflammation-related Parameters in Patients with COVID-19 Pneumonia. | journal = MedRxiv | date = January 2020 | doi = 10.1101/2020.02.25.20025643 }}</ref>\n\n== Function ==\n\n* IL-6 is an important mediator of [[fever]] and of the [[acute phase response]]. \n* It is capable of crossing the [[blood-brain barrier]]<ref name=\"pmid7845624\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Banks WA, Kastin AJ, Gutierrez EG | title = Penetration of interleukin-6 across the murine blood-brain barrier | journal = Neuroscience Letters | volume = 179 | issue = 1\u20132 | pages = 53\u20136 | date = September 1994 | pmid = 7845624 | doi = 10.1016/0304-3940(94)90933-4 }}</ref> and initiating synthesis of [[Prostaglandin E2|PGE<sub>2</sub>]] in the [[hypothalamus]], thereby changing the body's temperature setpoint. \n* In muscle and fatty tissue, IL-6 stimulates energy mobilization that leads to increased body temperature. \n* IL-6 can be secreted by [[macrophages]] in response to specific microbial molecules, referred to as [[pathogen]]-associated molecular patterns ([[Pathogen-associated molecular pattern|PAMP]]s). These PAMPs bind to an important group of detection molecules of the [[innate immune system]], called [[pattern recognition receptor]]s (PRRs), including Toll-like receptors ([[Toll-like receptor|TLR]]s). These are present on the cell surface and intracellular compartments and induce intracellular signaling cascades that give rise to inflammatory cytokine production.\n* IL-6 is found in many supplemental cloning media such as [[briclone]]. \n* Inhibitors of IL-6 (including [[estrogen]]) are used to treat postmenopausal [[osteoporosis]]. \n* IL-6 is also produced by [[adipocytes]] and is thought to be a reason why obese individuals have higher endogeneous levels of [[C-reactive protein|CRP]].<ref name=\"Bastard27041999\">{{cite journal | title = Evidence for a Link Between Adipose Tissue Interleukin-6 Content and Serum C-Reactive Protein Concentrations in Obese Subjects | journal = Circulation | volume = 99 | issue = 16 | year = 1999 | pages = 2219\u20132222 | doi = 10.1161/circ.99.16.2219/c |vauthors = Bastard JP, Jardel C, Delattre J, Hainque B, Bruckert E, Oberlin F | pmid = 10217702}}</ref> \n* Intranasally administered IL-6 has been shown to improve sleep-associated [[memory consolidation|consolidation]] of emotional memories.<ref name=\"pmid19546306\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Benedict C, Scheller J, Rose-John S, Born J, Marshall L | title = Enhancing influence of intranasal interleukin-6 on slow-wave activity and memory consolidation during sleep | journal = FASEB Journal | volume = 23 | issue = 10 | pages = 3629\u201336 | date = October 2009 | pmid = 19546306 | doi = 10.1096/fj.08-122853 }}</ref>\n* IL-6 is responsible for stimulating acute phase protein synthesis, as well as the production of [[neutrophils]] in the bone marrow. It supports the growth of [[B cells]] and is antagonistic to regulatory T cells.\n* When psychologically stressed, the human body produces stress hormones like [[cortisol]], which are able to trigger interleukin-6 release into the circulation.<ref name=\"pmid10204970\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Cohen S, Doyle WJ, Skoner DP | title = Psychological stress, cytokine production, and severity of upper respiratory illness | journal = Psychosomatic Medicine | volume = 61 | issue = 2 | pages = 175\u201380 | year = 1999 | pmid = 10204970 | doi = 10.1097/00006842-199903000-00009 | url = http://www.psychosomaticmedicine.org/content/61/2/175.long#content-block }}</ref>\n\n== Role as myokine ==\n\nIL-6 is also considered a [[myokine]], a cytokine produced from muscle, which is elevated in response to muscle contraction.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Febbraio MA, Pedersen BK | title = Contraction-induced myokine production and release: is skeletal muscle an endocrine organ? | journal = Exercise and Sport Sciences Reviews | volume = 33 | issue = 3 | pages = 114\u20139 | date = July 2005 | pmid = 16006818 | doi = 10.1097/00003677-200507000-00003 }}</ref> It is significantly elevated with exercise, and precedes the appearance of other cytokines in the circulation.  During exercise, it is thought to act in a hormone-like manner to mobilize extracellular substrates and/or augment substrate delivery.<ref name=\"pmid15772055\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Petersen AM, Pedersen BK | title = The anti-inflammatory effect of exercise | journal = Journal of Applied Physiology | volume = 98 | issue = 4 | pages = 1154\u201362 | date = April 2005 | pmid = 15772055 | doi = 10.1152/japplphysiol.00164.2004 | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/3a0fe0cb9bc1318c610f7f0bc8f5d2759a6b4b04 }}</ref>\n\nIL-6 has extensive anti-inflammatory functions in its role as a [[myokine]]. IL-6 was the first myokine that was found to be secreted into the blood stream in response to muscle contractions.<ref name=\"pmid18923185\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Pedersen BK, Febbraio MA | title = Muscle as an endocrine organ: focus on muscle-derived interleukin-6 | journal = Physiological Reviews | volume = 88 | issue = 4 | pages = 1379\u2013406 | date = October 2008 | pmid = 18923185 | doi = 10.1152/physrev.90100.2007 | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/795c1a83f853edfba47628e63ce2d171fd0d2dd3 }}</ref> Aerobic exercise provokes a systemic cytokine response, including, for example, IL-6, IL-1 receptor antagonist (IL-1ra), and IL-10. IL-6 was serendipitously discovered as a myokine because of the observation that it increased in an exponential fashion proportional to the length of exercise and the amount of muscle mass engaged in the exercise. It has been consistently demonstrated that the plasma concentration of IL-6 increases during muscular exercise. This increase is followed by the appearance of IL-1ra and the anti-inflammatory cytokine IL-10. In general, the cytokine response to exercise and sepsis differs with regard to TNF-\u03b1. Thus, the cytokine response to exercise is not preceded by an increase in plasma-TNF-\u03b1. Following exercise, the basal plasma IL-6 concentration may increase up to 100-fold, but less dramatic increases are more frequent. The exercise-induced increase of plasma IL-6 occurs in an exponential manner and the peak IL-6 level is reached at the end of the exercise or shortly thereafter. It is the combination of mode, intensity, and duration of the exercise that determines the magnitude of the exercise-induced increase of plasma IL-6.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Pedersen BK | title = Muscle as a secretory organ | journal = Comprehensive Physiology | volume = 3 | issue = 3 | pages = 1337\u201362 | date = July 2013 | pmid = 23897689 | doi = 10.1002/cphy.c120033 | isbn = 9780470650714 }}</ref>\n\nIL-6 had previously been classified as a proinflammatory cytokine. Therefore, it was first thought that the exercise-induced IL-6 response was related to muscle damage.<ref name=\"pmid9130176\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Bruunsgaard H, Galbo H, Halkjaer-Kristensen J, Johansen TL, MacLean DA, Pedersen BK | title = Exercise-induced increase in serum interleukin-6 in humans is related to muscle damage | journal = The Journal of Physiology | volume = 499 ( Pt 3) | issue = 3 | pages = 833\u201341 | date = March 1997 | pmid = 9130176 | pmc = 1159298 | doi = 10.1113/jphysiol.1997.sp021972 }}</ref> However, it has become evident that eccentric exercise is not associated with a larger increase in plasma IL-6 than exercise involving concentric \"nondamaging\" muscle contractions. This finding clearly demonstrates that muscle damage is not required to provoke an increase in plasma IL-6 during exercise. As a matter of fact, eccentric exercise may result in a delayed peak and a much slower decrease of plasma IL-6 during recovery.<ref name=\"pmid23897689\">{{cite book | vauthors = Pedersen BK | title = Muscle as a secretory organ | journal = Comprehensive Physiology | volume = 3 | issue = 3 | pages = 1337\u201362 | date = July 2013 | pmid = 23897689 | doi = 10.1002/cphy.c120033 | isbn = 9780470650714 }}</ref>\n\nRecent work has shown that both upstream and downstream signalling pathways for IL-6 differ markedly between myocytes and macrophages. It appears that unlike IL-6 signalling in macrophages, which is dependent upon activation of the NF\u03baB signalling pathway, intramuscular IL-6 expression is regulated by a network of signalling cascades, including the Ca2+/NFAT and glycogen/p38 MAPK pathways. Thus, when IL-6 is signalling in monocytes or macrophages, it creates a pro-inflammatory response, whereas IL-6 activation and signalling in muscle is totally\nindependent of a preceding TNF-response or NF\u03baB activation, and is anti-inflammatory.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Brandt C, Pedersen BK | title = The role of exercise-induced myokines in muscle homeostasis and the defense against chronic diseases | journal = Journal of Biomedicine & Biotechnology | volume = 2010 | issue =  | pages = 520258 | year = 2010 | pmid = 20224659 | doi = 10.1155/2010/520258 | pmc = 2836182 }}</ref>\n\nIL-6, among an increasing number of other recently identified myokines, thus remains an important topic in [[myokine]] research. It appears in muscle tissue and in the circulation during exercise at levels up to one hundred times basal rates, as noted, and is seen as having a beneficial impact on health and bodily functioning when elevated in response to [[physical exercise]].<ref name=\"pmid23663276\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Mu\u00f1oz-C\u00e1noves P, Scheele C, Pedersen BK, Serrano AL | title = Interleukin-6 myokine signaling in skeletal muscle: a double-edged sword? | journal = The FEBS Journal | volume = 280 | issue = 17 | pages = 4131\u201348 | date = September 2013 | pmid = 23663276 | pmc = 4163639 | doi = 10.1111/febs.12338 }}</ref> IL-6 was the first myokine that was found to be secreted into the blood stream in response to muscle contractions.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Pedersen BK, Febbraio MA | title = Muscle as an endocrine organ: focus on muscle-derived interleukin-6 | journal = Physiological Reviews | volume = 88 | issue = 4 | pages = 1379\u2013406 | date = October 2008 | pmid = 18923185 | doi = 10.1152/physrev.90100.2007 }}</ref>\n\n== Receptor ==\n\n{{main|Interleukin-6 receptor}}\nIL-6 signals through a cell-surface [[type I cytokine receptor]] complex consisting of the ligand-binding IL-6R\u03b1 chain ([[CD126]]), and the signal-transducing component [[gp130]] (also called CD130). CD130 is the common signal transducer for several cytokines including [[leukemia inhibitory factor]] (LIF), [[ciliary neurotropic factor]], [[oncostatin M]], [[interleukin 11|IL-11]] and [[cardiotrophin-1]], and is almost ubiquitously expressed in most tissues. In contrast, the expression of CD126 is restricted to certain tissues. As IL-6 interacts with its receptor, it triggers the gp130 and IL-6R proteins to form a complex, thus activating the receptor. These complexes bring together the [[intracellular]] regions of gp130 to initiate a signal transduction cascade through certain [[transcription factors]], [[Janus kinase]]s (JAKs) and Signal Transducers and Activators of Transcription ([[STAT protein|STATs]]).<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Heinrich PC, Behrmann I, M\u00fcller-Newen G, Schaper F, Graeve L | title = Interleukin-6-type cytokine signalling through the gp130/Jak/STAT pathway | journal = The Biochemical Journal | volume = 334 ( Pt 2) | issue = Pt 2 | pages = 297\u2013314 | date = September 1998 | pmid = 9716487 | pmc = 1219691 | doi = 10.1042/bj3340297 }}</ref>\n\nIL-6 is probably the best-studied of the cytokines that use [[gp130]], also known as IL-6 signal transducer (IL6ST),  in their signalling complexes. Other cytokines that signal through receptors containing gp130 are [[Interleukin 11]] (IL-11), [[Interleukin 27]] (IL-27), [[ciliary neurotrophic factor]] (CNTF), [[cardiotrophin-1]] (CT-1), [[CLCF1|cardiotrophin-like cytokine]] (CLC), [[leukemia inhibitory factor]] (LIF), [[oncostatin M]] (OSM), [[Kaposi's sarcoma-associated herpesvirus]] interleukin 6-like protein ([[KSHV-IL6]]).<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Kishimoto T, Akira S, Narazaki M, Taga T | title = Interleukin-6 family of cytokines and gp130 | journal = Blood | volume = 86 | issue = 4 | pages = 1243\u201354 | date = August 1995 | pmid = 7632928 | doi = 10.1182/blood.V86.4.1243.bloodjournal8641243 }}</ref> These cytokines are commonly referred to as the ''IL-6 like'' or ''gp130 utilising'' cytokines <ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Heinrich PC, Behrmann I, Haan S, Hermanns HM, M\u00fcller-Newen G, Schaper F | title = Principles of interleukin (IL)-6-type cytokine signalling and its regulation | journal = The Biochemical Journal | volume = 374 | issue = Pt 1 | pages = 1\u201320 | date = August 2003 | pmid = 12773095 | pmc = 1223585 | doi = 10.1042/BJ20030407 }}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the membrane-bound receptor, a soluble form of IL-6R (sIL-6R) has been purified from human serum and urine. Many neuronal cells are unresponsive to stimulation by IL-6 alone, but differentiation and survival of neuronal cells can be mediated through the action of sIL-6R. The sIL-6R/IL-6 complex can stimulate neurites outgrowth and promote survival of neurons and, hence, may be important in nerve regeneration through remyelination.\n\n==  Interactions ==\n\nInterleukin-6 has been shown to [[Protein-protein interaction|interact]] with [[interleukin-6 receptor]],<ref name=\"pmid14557255\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Schwantner A, Dingley AJ, Ozbek S, Rose-John S, Gr\u00f6tzinger J | title = Direct determination of the interleukin-6 binding epitope of the interleukin-6 receptor by NMR spectroscopy | journal = The Journal of Biological Chemistry | volume = 279 | issue = 1 | pages = 571\u20136 | date = January 2004 | pmid = 14557255 | doi = 10.1074/jbc.M311019200 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid12643274\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Schuster B, Kovaleva M, Sun Y, Regenhard P, Matthews V, Gr\u00f6tzinger J, Rose-John S, Kallen KJ | display-authors = 6 | title = Signaling of human ciliary neurotrophic factor (CNTF) revisited. The interleukin-6 receptor can serve as an alpha-receptor for CTNF | journal = The Journal of Biological Chemistry | volume = 278 | issue = 11 | pages = 9528\u201335 | date = March 2003 | pmid = 12643274 | doi = 10.1074/jbc.M210044200 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid2788034\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Taga T, Hibi M, Hirata Y, Yamasaki K, Yasukawa K, Matsuda T, Hirano T, Kishimoto T | display-authors = 6 | title = Interleukin-6 triggers the association of its receptor with a possible signal transducer, gp130 | journal = Cell | volume = 58 | issue = 3 | pages = 573\u201381 | date = August 1989 | pmid = 2788034 | doi = 10.1016/0092-8674(89)90438-8 }}</ref> [[glycoprotein 130]],<ref name=\"pmid15989626\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Kallen KJ, zum B\u00fcschenfelde KH, Rose-John S | title = The therapeutic potential of interleukin-6 hyperagonists and antagonists | journal = Expert Opinion on Investigational Drugs | volume = 6 | issue = 3 | pages = 237\u201366 | date = March 1997 | pmid = 15989626 | doi = 10.1517/13543784.6.3.237 }}</ref> and [[Galectin-3]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Gordon-Alonso M, Bruger AM, van der Bruggen P | title = Extracellular galectins as controllers of cytokines in hematological cancer | journal = Blood | volume = 132 | issue = 5 | pages = 484\u2013491 | date = August 2018 | pmid = 29875102 | pmc = 6073326 | doi = 10.1182/blood-2018-04-846014 }}</ref>\n\nThere is considerable functional overlap and interaction between Substance P (SP), the natural ligand for the neurokinin type 1 receptor (NK1R, a mediator of immunomodulatory activity) and IL-6.\n\n== Role in disease ==\n\nIL-6 stimulates the inflammatory and auto-immune processes in many diseases such as [[diabetes]],<ref name=\"pmid16306329\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Kristiansen OP, Mandrup-Poulsen T | title = Interleukin-6 and diabetes: the good, the bad, or the indifferent? | journal = Diabetes | volume = 54 Suppl 2 | issue =  | pages = S114-24 | date = December 2005 | pmid = 16306329 | doi = 10.2337/diabetes.54.suppl_2.S114 }}</ref> [[atherosclerosis]],<ref name=\"pmid17684929\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Dubi\u0144ski A, Zdrojewicz Z | title = [The role of interleukin-6 in development and progression of atherosclerosis] | language = Polish | journal = Polski Merkuriusz Lekarski | volume = 22 | issue = 130 | pages = 291\u20134 | date = April 2007 | pmid = 17684929 | doi =  }}</ref> [[Major depressive disorder|depression]],<ref name=\"pmid 20015486\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Dowlati Y, Herrmann N, Swardfager W, Liu H, Sham L, Reim EK, Lanct\u00f4t KL | title = A meta-analysis of cytokines in major depression | journal = Biological Psychiatry | volume = 67 | issue = 5 | pages = 446\u201357 | date = March 2010 | pmid = 20015486 | doi = 10.1016/j.biopsych.2009.09.033 }}</ref> [[Alzheimer's Disease]],<ref name=\"pmid 20692646\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Swardfager W, Lanct\u00f4t K, Rothenburg L, Wong A, Cappell J, Herrmann N | title = A meta-analysis of cytokines in Alzheimer's disease | journal = Biological Psychiatry | volume = 68 | issue = 10 | pages = 930\u201341 | date = November 2010 | pmid = 20692646 | doi = 10.1016/j.biopsych.2010.06.012 }}</ref> [[systemic lupus erythematosus]],<ref name=\"pmid15230289\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Tackey E, Lipsky PE, Illei GG | title = Rationale for interleukin-6 blockade in systemic lupus erythematosus | journal = Lupus | volume = 13 | issue = 5 | pages = 339\u201343 | year = 2004 | pmid = 15230289 | pmc = 2014821 | doi = 10.1191/0961203304lu1023oa }}</ref> [[multiple myeloma]],<ref name=\"pmid10816321\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Gad\u00f3 K, Domj\u00e1n G, Hegyesi H, Falus A | title = Role of INTERLEUKIN-6 in the pathogenesis of multiple myeloma | journal = Cell Biology International | volume = 24 | issue = 4 | pages = 195\u2013209 | year = 2000 | pmid = 10816321 | doi = 10.1006/cbir.2000.0497 }}</ref> [[prostate cancer]],<ref name=\"pmid11312117\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Smith PC, Hobisch A, Lin DL, Culig Z, Keller ET | title = Interleukin-6 and prostate cancer progression | journal = Cytokine & Growth Factor Reviews | volume = 12 | issue = 1 | pages = 33\u201340 | date = March 2001 | pmid = 11312117 | doi = 10.1016/S1359-6101(00)00021-6 }}</ref> [[Beh\u00e7et's disease]],<ref name=\"pmid23257520\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hirohata S, Kikuchi H | title = Changes in biomarkers focused on differences in disease course or treatment in patients with neuro-Beh\u00e7et's disease | journal = Internal Medicine | volume = 51 | issue = 24 | pages = 3359\u201365 | date = Dec 2012 | pmid = 23257520 | doi = 10.2169/internalmedicine.51.8583 }}</ref> and [[rheumatoid arthritis]].<ref name=\"pmid16582692\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Nishimoto N | title = Interleukin-6 in rheumatoid arthritis | journal = Current Opinion in Rheumatology | volume = 18 | issue = 3 | pages = 277\u201381 | date = May 2006 | pmid = 16582692 | doi = 10.1097/01.bor.0000218949.19860.d1 }}</ref>\n\nHence, there is an interest in developing [[anti-IL-6]] agents as therapy against many of these diseases.<ref name=\"pmid16083340\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Barton BE | title = Interleukin-6 and new strategies for the treatment of cancer, hyperproliferative diseases and paraneoplastic syndromes | journal = Expert Opinion on Therapeutic Targets | volume = 9 | issue = 4 | pages = 737\u201352 | date = August 2005 | pmid = 16083340 | doi = 10.1517/14728222.9.4.737 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid16899109\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Smolen JS, Maini RN | title = Interleukin-6: a new therapeutic target | journal = Arthritis Research & Therapy | volume = 8 Suppl 2 | issue = Suppl 2 | pages = S5 | year = 2006 | pmid = 16899109 | pmc = 3226077 | doi = 10.1186/ar1969 }}</ref> The first such is [[tocilizumab]], which has been approved for [[rheumatoid arthritis]],<ref name=\"EmeryKeystone2008\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Emery P, Keystone E, Tony HP, Cantagrel A, van Vollenhoven R, Sanchez A, Alecock E, Lee J, Kremer J | display-authors = 6 | title = IL-6 receptor inhibition with tocilizumab improves treatment outcomes in patients with rheumatoid arthritis refractory to anti-tumour necrosis factor biologicals: results from a 24-week multicentre randomised placebo-controlled trial | journal = Annals of the Rheumatic Diseases | volume = 67 | issue = 11 | pages = 1516\u201323 | date = November 2008 | pmid = 18625622 | pmc = 3811149 | doi = 10.1136/ard.2008.092932 }}</ref> [[Castleman's disease]]<ref name=\"Nishimoto2005\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Nishimoto N, Kanakura Y, Aozasa K, Johkoh T, Nakamura M, Nakano S, Nakano N, Ikeda Y, Sasaki T, Nishioka K, Hara M, Taguchi H, Kimura Y, Kato Y, Asaoku H, Kumagai S, Kodama F, Nakahara H, Hagihara K, Yoshizaki K, Kishimoto T | display-authors = 6 | title = Humanized anti-interleukin-6 receptor antibody treatment of multicentric Castleman disease | journal = Blood | volume = 106 | issue = 8 | pages = 2627\u201332 | date = October 2005 | pmid = 15998837 | doi = 10.1182/blood-2004-12-4602 }}</ref> and [[systemic juvenile idiopathic arthritis]].<ref name=\"YokotaImagawa2008\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Yokota S, Imagawa T, Mori M, Miyamae T, Aihara Y, Takei S, Iwata N, Umebayashi H, Murata T, Miyoshi M, Tomiita M, Nishimoto N, Kishimoto T | display-authors = 6 | title = Efficacy and safety of tocilizumab in patients with systemic-onset juvenile idiopathic arthritis: a randomised, double-blind, placebo-controlled, withdrawal phase III trial | journal = Lancet | volume = 371 | issue = 9617 | pages = 998\u20131006 | date = March 2008 | pmid = 18358927 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(08)60454-7 }}</ref>  Others are in clinical trials.<ref name=N-2013>[http://www.nature.com/nm/journal/v19/n10/full/nm1013-1193.html First IL-6\u2013blocking drug nears approval for rare blood disorder], Nature Medicine, October 7, 2013</ref>\n\n===Rheumatoid arthritis===\nThe first FDA approved [[anti-IL-6]] treatment was for rheumatoid arthritis.\n\n=== Cancer ===\n[[Anti-IL-6]] therapy was initially developed for treatment of [[autoimmune diseases]], but due to the role of IL-6 in chronic inflammation, IL-6 blockade was also evaluated for cancer treatment.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Korneev KV, Atretkhany KN, Drutskaya MS, Grivennikov SI, Kuprash DV, Nedospasov SA | title = TLR-signaling and proinflammatory cytokines as drivers of tumorigenesis | journal = Cytokine | volume = 89 | pages = 127\u2013135 | date = January 2017 | pmid = 26854213 | doi = 10.1016/j.cyto.2016.01.021 }}</ref><ref name=\"AnestakisPetanidis2015\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Anestakis D, Petanidis S, Kalyvas S, Nday CM, Tsave O, Kioseoglou E, Salifoglou A | title = Mechanisms and applications of interleukins in cancer immunotherapy | journal = International Journal of Molecular Sciences | volume = 16 | issue = 1 | pages = 1691\u2013710 | date = January 2015 | pmid = 25590298 | pmc = 4307328 | doi = 10.3390/ijms16011691 }}</ref> IL-6 was seen to have roles in tumor microenvironment regulation,<ref name=\"LiMo2012\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Li J, Mo HY, Xiong G, Zhang L, He J, Huang ZF, Liu ZW, Chen QY, Du ZM, Zheng LM, Qian CN, Zeng YX | display-authors = 6 | title = Tumor microenvironment macrophage inhibitory factor directs the accumulation of interleukin-17-producing tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes and predicts favorable survival in nasopharyngeal carcinoma patients | journal = The Journal of Biological Chemistry | volume = 287 | issue = 42 | pages = 35484\u201395 | date = October 2012 | pmid = 22893706 | pmc = 3471767 | doi = 10.1074/jbc.M112.367532 }}</ref> production of [[breast cancer]] stem cell-like cells,<ref name=\"Yuan2011\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Xie G, Yao Q, Liu Y, Du S, Liu A, Guo Z, Sun A, Ruan J, Chen L, Ye C, Yuan Y | display-authors = 6 | title = IL-6-induced epithelial-mesenchymal transition promotes the generation of breast cancer stem-like cells analogous to mammosphere cultures | journal = International Journal of Oncology | volume = 40 | issue = 4 | pages = 1171\u20139 | date = April 2012 | pmid = 22134360 | pmc = 3584811 | doi = 10.3892/ijo.2011.1275 }}</ref> metastasis through down-regulation of E-cadherin,<ref name=\"MiaoLiu2014\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Miao JW, Liu LJ, Huang J | title = Interleukin-6-induced epithelial-mesenchymal transition through signal transducer and activator of transcription 3 in human cervical carcinoma | journal = International Journal of Oncology | volume = 45 | issue = 1 | pages = 165\u201376 | date = July 2014 | pmid = 24806843 | doi = 10.3892/ijo.2014.2422 }}</ref> and alteration of DNA methylation in oral cancer.<ref name=\"GascheHoffmann2011\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Gasche JA, Hoffmann J, Boland CR, Goel A | title = Interleukin-6 promotes tumorigenesis by altering DNA methylation in oral cancer cells | journal = International Journal of Cancer | volume = 129 | issue = 5 | pages = 1053\u201363 | date = September 2011 | pmid = 21710491 | pmc = 3110561 | doi = 10.1002/ijc.25764 }}</ref>\n\nAdvanced/[[metastatic cancer]] patients have higher levels of IL-6 in their blood.<ref name=\"urlMedscape.com Log In\">{{cite web | url = http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/537309 | title =  Cancer Patients Typically Have Increased Interleukin-6 Levels | date = 2006-06-26 | format = | work = American Society of Clinical Oncology 2006 Annual Meeting, Abstracts 8632 and 8633 | publisher = Medscape.com }}</ref> One example of this is [[pancreatic cancer]], with noted elevation of IL-6 present in patients correlating with poor survival rates.<ref name=\"BelloneSmirne2005\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Bellone G, Smirne C, Mauri FA, Tonel E, Carbone A, Buffolino A, Dughera L, Robecchi A, Pirisi M, Emanuelli G | display-authors = 6 | title = Cytokine expression profile in human pancreatic carcinoma cells and in surgical specimens: implications for survival | journal = Cancer Immunology, Immunotherapy | volume = 55 | issue = 6 | pages = 684\u201398 | date = June 2006 | pmid = 16094523 | doi = 10.1007/s00262-005-0047-0 }}</ref>\n\n=== Infectious diseases ===\n\n====Enterovirus 71====\nHigh IL-6 levels are associated with the development of [[encephalitis]] in children and immunodeficient [[Laboratory mouse|mouse models]] infected with [[Enterovirus 71]]; this highly contagious virus normally causes a milder illness called [[Hand, foot, and mouth disease]] but can cause life-threatening encephalitis in some cases. EV71 patients with a certain [[gene polymorphism]] in IL-6 also appear to be more susceptible to developing encephalitis.\n\n=== Epigenetic modifications  ===\n\nIL-6 has been shown to lead to several neurological diseases through its impact on [[epigenetics|epigenetic]] modification within the brain.<ref name=\"pmid17913903\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Smith SE, Li J, Garbett K, Mirnics K, Patterson PH | title = Maternal immune activation alters fetal brain development through interleukin-6 | journal = The Journal of Neuroscience | volume = 27 | issue = 40 | pages = 10695\u2013702 | date = October 2007 | pmid = 17913903 | pmc = 2387067 | doi = 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.2178-07.2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid19029285\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Kundakovic M, Chen Y, Guidotti A, Grayson DR | title = The reelin and GAD67 promoters are activated by epigenetic drugs that facilitate the disruption of local repressor complexes | journal = Molecular Pharmacology | volume = 75 | issue = 2 | pages = 342\u201354 | date = February 2009 | pmid = 19029285 | pmc = 2684898 | doi = 10.1124/mol.108.051763 }}</ref> IL-6 activates the [[Phosphoinositide 3-kinase]] (PI3K) pathway, and a downstream target of this pathway is the [[AKT|protein kinase B]] (PKB) (Hodge et al., 2007). IL-6 activated PKB can phosphorylate the nuclear localization signal on [[DNMT1|DNA methyltransferase-1]] (DNMT1).<ref name=\"pmid18204201\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hodge DR, Cho E, Copeland TD, Guszczynski T, Yang E, Seth AK, Farrar WL | title = IL-6 enhances the nuclear translocation of DNA cytosine-5-methyltransferase 1 (DNMT1) via phosphorylation of the nuclear localization sequence by the AKT kinase | journal = Cancer Genomics & Proteomics | volume = 4 | issue = 6 | pages = 387\u201398 | year = 2007 | pmid = 18204201 | doi =  }}</ref> This phosphorylation causes movement of DNMT1 to the nucleus, where it can be transcribed.<ref name=\"pmid18204201\"/> DNMT1 recruits other DNMTs, including DNMT3A and DNMT3B, which, as a complex, recruit [[HDAC1]].<ref name=\"pmid19029285\"/> This complex adds methyl groups to [[CpG islands]] on gene promoters, repressing the chromatin structure surrounding the DNA sequence and inhibiting transcriptional machinery from accessing the gene to induce transcription.<ref name=\"pmid19029285\"/> Increased IL-6, therefore, can hypermethylate DNA sequences and subsequently decrease gene expression through its effects on DNMT1 expression.<ref name=\"pmid20354000\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Foran E, Garrity-Park MM, Mureau C, Newell J, Smyrk TC, Limburg PJ, Egan LJ | title = Upregulation of DNA methyltransferase-mediated gene silencing, anchorage-independent growth, and migration of colon cancer cells by interleukin-6 | journal = Molecular Cancer Research | volume = 8 | issue = 4 | pages = 471\u201381 | date = April 2010 | pmid = 20354000 | doi = 10.1158/1541-7786.MCR-09-0496 }}</ref>\n\n==== Schizophrenia ====\n\nThe induction of epigenetic modification by IL-6 has been proposed as a mechanism in the pathology of schizophrenia through the hypermethylation and repression of the [[Glutamate decarboxylase|GAD67]] promoter.<ref name=\"pmid19029285\"/> This hypermethylation may potentially lead to the decreased GAD67 levels seen in the brains of people with schizophrenia.<ref name=\"pmid11074872\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Guidotti A, Auta J, Davis JM, Di-Giorgi-Gerevini V, Dwivedi Y, Grayson DR, Impagnatiello F, Pandey G, Pesold C, Sharma R, Uzunov D, Costa E, DiGiorgi Gerevini V | display-authors = 6 | title = Decrease in reelin and glutamic acid decarboxylase67 (GAD67) expression in schizophrenia and bipolar disorder: a postmortem brain study | journal = Archives of General Psychiatry | volume = 57 | issue = 11 | pages = 1061\u20139 | date = November 2000 | pmid = 11074872 | doi = 10.1001/archpsyc.57.11.1061 }}</ref> GAD67 may be involved in the pathology of schizophrenia through its effect on [[gamma-Aminobutyric acid|GABA]] levels and on [[neural oscillation]]s.<ref name=\"pmid22806213\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Gandal MJ, Sisti J, Klook K, Ortinski PI, Leitman V, Liang Y, Thieu T, Anderson R, Pierce RC, Jonak G, Gur RE, Carlson G, Siegel SJ | display-authors = 6 | title = GABAB-mediated rescue of altered excitatory-inhibitory balance, gamma synchrony and behavioral deficits following constitutive NMDAR-hypofunction | journal = Translational Psychiatry | volume = 2 | issue = 7 | pages = e142 | date = July 2012 | pmid = 22806213 | pmc = 3410621 | doi = 10.1038/tp.2012.69 }}</ref> Neural oscillations occur when inhibitory GABAergic neurons fire synchronously and cause inhibition of a multitude of target excitatory neurons at the same time, leading to a cycle of inhibition and disinhibition.<ref name=\"pmid22806213\"/> These neural oscillations are impaired in schizophrenia, and these alterations may be responsible for both positive and negative symptoms of schizophrenia.<ref name=\"pmid20087360\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Uhlhaas PJ, Singer W | title = Abnormal neural oscillations and synchrony in schizophrenia | journal = Nature Reviews. Neuroscience | volume = 11 | issue = 2 | pages = 100\u201313 | date = February 2010 | pmid = 20087360 | doi = 10.1038/nrn2774 }}</ref>\n\n==== Depression and major depressive disorder ====\n{{See also|Epigenetics of depression#Brain-derived neurotrophic factor, Epigenetics of schizophrenia#Methylation of BDNF}}\nThe epigenetic effects IL-6 have also been implicated in the pathology of [[Depression (mood)|depression]]. The effects of IL-6 on depression are mediated through the repression of [[brain-derived neurotrophic factor]] (BDNF) expression in the brain; DNMT1 hypermethylates the BDNF promoter and reduces BDNF levels.<ref name=\"pmid18536530\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Sharma RP, Tun N, Grayson DR | title = Depolarization induces downregulation of DNMT1 and DNMT3a in primary cortical cultures | journal = Epigenetics | volume = 3 | issue = 2 | pages = 74\u201380 | year = 2008 | pmid = 18536530 | doi = 10.4161/epi.3.2.6103 }}</ref> Altered BDNF function has been implicated in depression,<ref name=\"pmid16343697\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hwang JP, Tsai SJ, Hong CJ, Yang CH, Lirng JF, Yang YM | title = The Val66Met polymorphism of the brain-derived neurotrophic-factor gene is associated with geriatric depression | journal = Neurobiology of Aging | volume = 27 | issue = 12 | pages = 1834\u20137 | date = December 2006 | pmid = 16343697 | doi = 10.1016/j.neurobiolaging.2005.10.013 }}</ref> which is likely due to epigenetic modification following IL-6 upregulation.<ref name=\"pmid18536530\"/> BDNF is a neutrophic factor implicated in spine formation, density, and morphology on neurons.<ref name=\"pmid15882774\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Ethell IM, Pasquale EB | title = Molecular mechanisms of dendritic spine development and remodeling | journal = Progress in Neurobiology | volume = 75 | issue = 3 | pages = 161\u2013205 | date = February 2005 | pmid = 15882774 | doi = 10.1016/j.pneurobio.2005.02.003 }}</ref> Downregulation of BDNF, therefore, may cause decreased connectivity in the brain. Depression is marked by altered connectivity, in particular between the [[anterior cingulate cortex]] and several other limbic areas, such as the [[hippocampus]].<ref name=\"pmid17210143\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Greicius MD, Flores BH, Menon V, Glover GH, Solvason HB, Kenna H, Reiss AL, Schatzberg AF | display-authors = 6 | title = Resting-state functional connectivity in major depression: abnormally increased contributions from subgenual cingulate cortex and thalamus | journal = Biological Psychiatry | volume = 62 | issue = 5 | pages = 429\u201337 | date = September 2007 | pmid = 17210143 | pmc = 2001244 | doi = 10.1016/j.biopsych.2006.09.020 }}</ref> The anterior cingulate cortex is responsible for detecting incongruences between expectation and perceived experience.<ref name=\"pmid16819523\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Somerville LH, Heatherton TF, Kelley WM | title = Anterior cingulate cortex responds differentially to expectancy violation and social rejection | journal = Nature Neuroscience | volume = 9 | issue = 8 | pages = 1007\u20138 | date = August 2006 | pmid = 16819523 | doi = 10.1038/nn1728 }}</ref> Altered connectivity of the anterior cingulate cortex in depression, therefore, may cause altered emotions following certain experiences, leading to depressive reactions.<ref name=\"pmid16819523\"/> This altered connectivity is mediated by IL-6 and its effect on epigenetic regulation of BDNF.<ref name=\"pmid18536530\"/>\n\nAdditional preclinical and clinical data, suggest that [[Substance P]] [SP] and IL-6 may act in concert to promote major depression. SP, a hybrid neurotransmitter-cytokine, is co-transmitted with BDNF through paleo-spinothalamic circuitry from the periphery with collaterals into key areas of the limbic system. However, both IL6 and SP mitigate expression of BDNF in brain regions associated with negative affect and memory. SP and IL6 both relax tight junctions of the blood brain barrier, such that effects seen in fMRI experiments with these molecules may be a bidirectional mix of neuronal, glial, capillary, synaptic, paracrine, or endocrine-like effects. At the cellular level, SP is noted to increase expression of interleukin-6 (IL-6) through PI-3K, p42/44 and p38 MAP kinase pathways. Data suggest that nuclear translocation of NF-\u03baB regulates IL-6 overexpression in SP-stimulated cells.<ref name=\"pmid14654230\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Azzolina A, Bongiovanni A, Lampiasi N | title = Substance P induces TNF-alpha and IL-6 production through NF kappa B in peritoneal mast cells | journal = Biochimica et Biophysica Acta | volume = 1643 | issue = 1\u20133 | pages = 75\u201383 | date = December 2003 | pmid = 14654230 | doi = 10.1016/j.bbamcr.2003.09.003 }}</ref> This is of key interest as: 1) a meta-analysis indicates an association of major depressive disorder, C-reactive protein and IL6 plasma concentrations,<ref name=\"pmid26065825\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Haapakoski R, Mathieu J, Ebmeier KP, Alenius H, Kivim\u00e4ki M | title = Cumulative meta-analysis of interleukins 6 and 1\u03b2, tumour necrosis factor \u03b1 and C-reactive protein in patients with major depressive disorder | journal = Brain, Behavior, and Immunity | volume = 49 | issue =  | pages = 206\u201315 | date = October 2015 | pmid = 26065825 | pmc = 4566946 | doi = 10.1016/j.bbi.2015.06.001 }}</ref> 2) NK1R antagonists [five molecules] studied by 3 independent groups in over 2000 patients from 1998-2013 validate the mechanism as dose-related, fully effective antidepressant,  with a unique safety profile.<ref name=\"pmid23539641\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Ratti E, Bettica P, Alexander R, Archer G, Carpenter D, Evoniuk G, Gomeni R, Lawson E, Lopez M, Millns H, Rabiner EA, Trist D, Trower M, Zamuner S, Krishnan R, Fava M | display-authors = 6 | title = Full central neurokinin-1 receptor blockade is required for efficacy in depression: evidence from orvepitant clinical studies | journal = Journal of Psychopharmacology | volume = 27 | issue = 5 | pages = 424\u201334 | date = May 2013 | pmid = 23539641 | doi = 10.1177/0269881113480990 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid9733503\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Kramer MS, Cutler N, Feighner J, Shrivastava R, Carman J, Sramek JJ, Reines SA, Liu G, Snavely D, Wyatt-Knowles E, Hale JJ, Mills SG, MacCoss M, Swain CJ, Harrison T, Hill RG, Hefti F, Scolnick EM, Cascieri MA, Chicchi GG, Sadowski S, Williams AR, Hewson L, Smith D, Carlson EJ, Hargreaves RJ, Rupniak NM | display-authors = 6 | title = Distinct mechanism for antidepressant activity by blockade of central substance P receptors | journal = Science | volume = 281 | issue = 5383 | pages = 1640\u20135 | date = September 1998 | pmid = 9733503 | doi = 10.1126/science.281.5383.1640 | bibcode = 1998Sci...281.1640K }}</ref> [[Aprepitant#Major Depression|(see Summary of NK1RAs in Major Depression)]], 3) the preliminary observation that plasma concentrations of IL6 are elevated in depressed patients with cancer,<ref name=\"pmid11481159\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Musselman DL, Miller AH, Porter MR, Manatunga A, Gao F, Penna S, Pearce BD, Landry J, Glover S, McDaniel JS, Nemeroff CB | display-authors = 6 | title = Higher than normal plasma interleukin-6 concentrations in cancer patients with depression: preliminary findings | journal = The American Journal of Psychiatry | volume = 158 | issue = 8 | pages = 1252\u20137 | date = August 2001 | pmid = 11481159 | doi = 10.1176/appi.ajp.158.8.1252 }}</ref> and 4) selective NK1RAs may eliminate endogenous SP stress-induced augmentation of IL-6 secretion pre-clinically.<ref name=\"pmid8642417\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Zhu GF, Chancellor-Freeland C, Berman AS, Kage R, Leeman SE, Beller DI, Black PH | title = Endogenous substance P mediates cold water stress-induced increase in interleukin-6 secretion from peritoneal macrophages | journal = The Journal of Neuroscience | volume = 16 | issue = 11 | pages = 3745\u201352 | date = June 1996 | pmid = 8642417 | pmc = 6578844 | doi = 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.16-11-03745.1996 }}</ref> These and many other reports suggest that a clinical study of a neutralizing IL-6 biological or drug based antagonist is likely warranted in patients with major depressive disorder, with or without co-morbid chronic inflammatory based illnesses; that the combination of NK1RAs and IL6 blockers may represent a new, potentially biomarkable approach to major depression, and possibly [[bipolar disorder]].\n\nThe IL-6 antibody [[sirukumab]] is now undergoing clinical trials against [[major depressive disorder]].<ref>{{ClinicalTrialsGov|NCT02473289|An Efficacy and Safety Study of Sirukumab in Participants With Major Depressive Disorder.}}</ref>\n\n===Asthma===\nObesity is a known risk factor in the development of severe asthma. Recent data suggests that the inflammation associated with obesity, potentially mediated by the cytokine IL6, plays a role in causing poor lung function and increased risk for developing asthma exacerbations.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Peters MC, McGrath KW, Hawkins GA, Hastie AT, Levy BD, Israel E, Phillips BR, Mauger DT, Comhair SA, Erzurum SC, Johansson MW, Jarjour NN, Coverstone AM, Castro M, Holguin F, Wenzel SE, Woodruff PG, Bleecker ER, Fahy JV | display-authors = 6 | title = Plasma interleukin-6 concentrations, metabolic dysfunction, and asthma severity: a cross-sectional analysis of two cohorts | journal = The Lancet. Respiratory Medicine | volume = 4 | issue = 7 | pages = 574\u2013584 | date = July 2016 | pmid = 27283230 | pmc = 5007068 | doi = 10.1016/S2213-2600(16)30048-0 }}</ref>\n\n== Protein superfamily ==\nInterleukin is the main member of the IL-6 superfamily ({{Pfam|PF00489}}), which also includes [[Granulocyte colony-stimulating factor|G-CSF]], [[Interleukin-23|IL23A]], and CLCF1. A viral version of IL6 is found in [[Kaposi's sarcoma-associated herpesvirus]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Suthaus J, Stuhlmann-Laeisz C, Tompkins VS, Rosean TR, Klapper W, Tosato G, Janz S, Scheller J, Rose-John S | display-authors = 6 | title = HHV-8-encoded viral IL-6 collaborates with mouse IL-6 in the development of multicentric Castleman disease in mice | journal = Blood | volume = 119 | issue = 22 | pages = 5173\u201381 | date = May 2012 | pmid = 22490805 | doi = 10.1182/blood-2011-09-377705 | pmc = 3370672 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.cancerindex.org/geneweb/IL6.htm IL-6 expression in various cancers]\n\n{{PDB Gallery|geneid=3569}}\n{{Interleukins}}\n{{Neurotrophic factors}}\n{{Interleukin receptor modulators}}\n\n[[Category:Interleukins]]\n[[Category:Osaka University research]]\n[[Category:Neurotrophic factors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox gene}}\n'''Interleukin 6''' ('''IL-6''') is an [[interleukin]] that acts as both a pro-inflammatory [[cytokine]] and an anti-inflammatory [[myokine]]. In humans, it is encoded by the ''IL6'' [[gene]].<ref name=\"pmid3294161\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Ferguson-Smith AC, Chen YF, Newman MS, May LT, Sehgal PB, Ruddle FH | title = Regional localization of the interferon-beta 2/B-cell stimulatory factor 2/hepatocyte stimulating factor gene to human chromosome 7p15-p21 | journal = Genomics | volume = 2 | issue = 3 | pages = 203\u20138 | date = April 1988 | pmid = 3294161 | doi = 10.1016/0888-7543(88)90003-1 }}</ref>\n\nIn addition, [[osteoblast]]s secrete IL-6 to stimulate [[osteoclast]] formation.  [[Smooth muscle cell]]s in the [[tunica media]] of many blood vessels also produce IL-6 as a pro-inflammatory [[cytokine]].  IL-6's role as an anti-inflammatory myokine is mediated through its inhibitory effects on [[TNF-alpha]] and [[IL1A|IL-1]], and activation of [[Interleukin 1 receptor antagonist|IL-1ra]] and [[Interleukin 10|IL-10]].\n\nThere is some early evidence that IL-6 can be used as an [[inflammatory markers|inflammatory marker]] for severe [[COVID-19]] infection with poor prognosis, in the context of the wider [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Raised troponin and interleukin-6 levels are associated with a poor prognosis in COVID-19 | url = https://cardiacrhythmnews.com/raised-troponin-and-interleukin-6-levels-are-associated-with-a-poor-prognosis-in-covid-19/ | date = 2 April 2020 | work = Cardiac Rhythm News }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Gong J, Dong H, Xia SQ, Huang YZ, Wang D, Zhao Y, Liu W, Tu S, Zhang M, Wang Q, Lu F | display-authors = 6 | title = Correlation Analysis Between Disease Severity and Inflammation-related Parameters in Patients with COVID-19 Pneumonia. | journal = MedRxiv | date = January 2020 | doi = 10.1101/2020.02.25.20025643 }}</ref>\n\n== Function ==\n\n* IL-6 is an important mediator of [[fever]] and of the [[acute phase response]]. \n* It is capable of crossing the [[blood-brain barrier]]<ref name=\"pmid7845624\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Banks WA, Kastin AJ, Gutierrez EG | title = Penetration of interleukin-6 across the murine blood-brain barrier | journal = Neuroscience Letters | volume = 179 | issue = 1\u20132 | pages = 53\u20136 | date = September 1994 | pmid = 7845624 | doi = 10.1016/0304-3940(94)90933-4 }}</ref> and initiating synthesis of [[Prostaglandin E2|PGE<sub>2</sub>]] in the [[hypothalamus]], thereby changing the body's temperature setpoint. \n* In muscle and fatty tissue, IL-6 stimulates energy mobilization that leads to increased body temperature. \n* IL-6 can be secreted by [[macrophages]] in response to specific microbial molecules, referred to as [[pathogen]]-associated molecular patterns ([[Pathogen-associated molecular pattern|PAMP]]s). These PAMPs bind to an important group of detection molecules of the [[innate immune system]], called [[pattern recognition receptor]]s (PRRs), including Toll-like receptors ([[Toll-like receptor|TLR]]s). These are present on the cell surface and intracellular compartments and induce intracellular signaling cascades that give rise to inflammatory cytokine production.\n* IL-6 is found in many supplemental cloning media such as [[briclone]]. \n* Inhibitors of IL-6 (including [[estrogen]]) are used to treat postmenopausal [[osteoporosis]]. \n* IL-6 is also produced by [[adipocytes]] and is thought to be a reason why obese individuals have higher endogeneous levels of [[C-reactive protein|CRP]].<ref name=\"Bastard27041999\">{{cite journal | title = Evidence for a Link Between Adipose Tissue Interleukin-6 Content and Serum C-Reactive Protein Concentrations in Obese Subjects | journal = Circulation | volume = 99 | issue = 16 | year = 1999 | pages = 2219\u20132222 | doi = 10.1161/01.CIR.99.16.2219.c  |vauthors=Bastard J, Jardel C, Delattre J, Hainque B, etal | doi-broken-date = 2020-04-11 }}</ref> \n* Intranasally administered IL-6 has been shown to improve sleep-associated [[memory consolidation|consolidation]] of emotional memories.<ref name=\"pmid19546306\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Benedict C, Scheller J, Rose-John S, Born J, Marshall L | title = Enhancing influence of intranasal interleukin-6 on slow-wave activity and memory consolidation during sleep | journal = FASEB Journal | volume = 23 | issue = 10 | pages = 3629\u201336 | date = October 2009 | pmid = 19546306 | doi = 10.1096/fj.08-122853 }}</ref>\n* IL-6 is responsible for stimulating acute phase protein synthesis, as well as the production of [[neutrophils]] in the bone marrow. It supports the growth of [[B cells]] and is antagonistic to regulatory T cells.\n* When psychologically stressed, the human body produces stress hormones like [[cortisol]], which are able to trigger interleukin-6 release into the circulation.<ref name=\"pmid10204970\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Cohen S, Doyle WJ, Skoner DP | title = Psychological stress, cytokine production, and severity of upper respiratory illness | journal = Psychosomatic Medicine | volume = 61 | issue = 2 | pages = 175\u201380 | year = 1999 | pmid = 10204970 | doi = 10.1097/00006842-199903000-00009 | url = http://www.psychosomaticmedicine.org/content/61/2/175.long#content-block }}</ref>\n\n== Role as myokine ==\n\nIL-6 is also considered a [[myokine]], a cytokine produced from muscle, which is elevated in response to muscle contraction.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Febbraio MA, Pedersen BK | title = Contraction-induced myokine production and release: is skeletal muscle an endocrine organ? | journal = Exercise and Sport Sciences Reviews | volume = 33 | issue = 3 | pages = 114\u20139 | date = July 2005 | pmid = 16006818 | doi = 10.1097/00003677-200507000-00003 }}</ref> It is significantly elevated with exercise, and precedes the appearance of other cytokines in the circulation.  During exercise, it is thought to act in a hormone-like manner to mobilize extracellular substrates and/or augment substrate delivery.<ref name=\"pmid15772055\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Petersen AM, Pedersen BK | title = The anti-inflammatory effect of exercise | journal = Journal of Applied Physiology | volume = 98 | issue = 4 | pages = 1154\u201362 | date = April 2005 | pmid = 15772055 | doi = 10.1152/japplphysiol.00164.2004 | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/3a0fe0cb9bc1318c610f7f0bc8f5d2759a6b4b04 }}</ref>\n\nIL-6 has extensive anti-inflammatory functions in its role as a [[myokine]]. IL-6 was the first myokine that was found to be secreted into the blood stream in response to muscle contractions.<ref name=\"pmid18923185\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Pedersen BK, Febbraio MA | title = Muscle as an endocrine organ: focus on muscle-derived interleukin-6 | journal = Physiological Reviews | volume = 88 | issue = 4 | pages = 1379\u2013406 | date = October 2008 | pmid = 18923185 | doi = 10.1152/physrev.90100.2007 | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/795c1a83f853edfba47628e63ce2d171fd0d2dd3 }}</ref> Aerobic exercise provokes a systemic cytokine response, including, for example, IL-6, IL-1 receptor antagonist (IL-1ra), and IL-10. IL-6 was serendipitously discovered as a myokine because of the observation that it increased in an exponential fashion proportional to the length of exercise and the amount of muscle mass engaged in the exercise. It has been consistently demonstrated that the plasma concentration of IL-6 increases during muscular exercise. This increase is followed by the appearance of IL-1ra and the anti-inflammatory cytokine IL-10. In general, the cytokine response to exercise and sepsis differs with regard to TNF-\u03b1. Thus, the cytokine response to exercise is not preceded by an increase in plasma-TNF-\u03b1. Following exercise, the basal plasma IL-6 concentration may increase up to 100-fold, but less dramatic increases are more frequent. The exercise-induced increase of plasma IL-6 occurs in an exponential manner and the peak IL-6 level is reached at the end of the exercise or shortly thereafter. It is the combination of mode, intensity, and duration of the exercise that determines the magnitude of the exercise-induced increase of plasma IL-6.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Pedersen BK | title = Muscle as a secretory organ | journal = Comprehensive Physiology | volume = 3 | issue = 3 | pages = 1337\u201362 | date = July 2013 | pmid = 23897689 | doi = 10.1002/cphy.c120033 | isbn = 9780470650714 }}</ref>\n\nIL-6 had previously been classified as a proinflammatory cytokine. Therefore, it was first thought that the exercise-induced IL-6 response was related to muscle damage.<ref name=\"pmid9130176\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Bruunsgaard H, Galbo H, Halkjaer-Kristensen J, Johansen TL, MacLean DA, Pedersen BK | title = Exercise-induced increase in serum interleukin-6 in humans is related to muscle damage | journal = The Journal of Physiology | volume = 499 ( Pt 3) | issue = 3 | pages = 833\u201341 | date = March 1997 | pmid = 9130176 | pmc = 1159298 | doi = 10.1113/jphysiol.1997.sp021972 }}</ref> However, it has become evident that eccentric exercise is not associated with a larger increase in plasma IL-6 than exercise involving concentric \"nondamaging\" muscle contractions. This finding clearly demonstrates that muscle damage is not required to provoke an increase in plasma IL-6 during exercise. As a matter of fact, eccentric exercise may result in a delayed peak and a much slower decrease of plasma IL-6 during recovery.<ref name=\"pmid23897689\">{{cite book | vauthors = Pedersen BK | title = Muscle as a secretory organ | journal = Comprehensive Physiology | volume = 3 | issue = 3 | pages = 1337\u201362 | date = July 2013 | pmid = 23897689 | doi = 10.1002/cphy.c120033 | isbn = 9780470650714 }}</ref>\n\nRecent work has shown that both upstream and downstream signalling pathways for IL-6 differ markedly between myocytes and macrophages. It appears that unlike IL-6 signalling in macrophages, which is dependent upon activation of the NF\u03baB signalling pathway, intramuscular IL-6 expression is regulated by a network of signalling cascades, including the Ca2+/NFAT and glycogen/p38 MAPK pathways. Thus, when IL-6 is signalling in monocytes or macrophages, it creates a pro-inflammatory response, whereas IL-6 activation and signalling in muscle is totally\nindependent of a preceding TNF-response or NF\u03baB activation, and is anti-inflammatory.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Brandt C, Pedersen BK | title = The role of exercise-induced myokines in muscle homeostasis and the defense against chronic diseases | journal = Journal of Biomedicine & Biotechnology | volume = 2010 | issue =  | pages = 520258 | year = 2010 | pmid = 20224659 | doi = 10.1155/2010/520258 | pmc = 2836182 }}</ref>\n\nIL-6, among an increasing number of other recently identified myokines, thus remains an important topic in [[myokine]] research. It appears in muscle tissue and in the circulation during exercise at levels up to one hundred times basal rates, as noted, and is seen as having a beneficial impact on health and bodily functioning when elevated in response to [[physical exercise]].<ref name=\"pmid23663276\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Mu\u00f1oz-C\u00e1noves P, Scheele C, Pedersen BK, Serrano AL | title = Interleukin-6 myokine signaling in skeletal muscle: a double-edged sword? | journal = The FEBS Journal | volume = 280 | issue = 17 | pages = 4131\u201348 | date = September 2013 | pmid = 23663276 | pmc = 4163639 | doi = 10.1111/febs.12338 }}</ref> IL-6 was the first myokine that was found to be secreted into the blood stream in response to muscle contractions.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Pedersen BK, Febbraio MA | title = Muscle as an endocrine organ: focus on muscle-derived interleukin-6 | journal = Physiological Reviews | volume = 88 | issue = 4 | pages = 1379\u2013406 | date = October 2008 | pmid = 18923185 | doi = 10.1152/physrev.90100.2007 }}</ref>\n\n== Receptor ==\n\n{{main|Interleukin-6 receptor}}\nIL-6 signals through a cell-surface [[type I cytokine receptor]] complex consisting of the ligand-binding IL-6R\u03b1 chain ([[CD126]]), and the signal-transducing component [[gp130]] (also called CD130). CD130 is the common signal transducer for several cytokines including [[leukemia inhibitory factor]] (LIF), [[ciliary neurotropic factor]], [[oncostatin M]], [[interleukin 11|IL-11]] and [[cardiotrophin-1]], and is almost ubiquitously expressed in most tissues. In contrast, the expression of CD126 is restricted to certain tissues. As IL-6 interacts with its receptor, it triggers the gp130 and IL-6R proteins to form a complex, thus activating the receptor. These complexes bring together the [[intracellular]] regions of gp130 to initiate a signal transduction cascade through certain [[transcription factors]], [[Janus kinase]]s (JAKs) and Signal Transducers and Activators of Transcription ([[STAT protein|STATs]]).<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Heinrich PC, Behrmann I, M\u00fcller-Newen G, Schaper F, Graeve L | title = Interleukin-6-type cytokine signalling through the gp130/Jak/STAT pathway | journal = The Biochemical Journal | volume = 334 ( Pt 2) | issue = Pt 2 | pages = 297\u2013314 | date = September 1998 | pmid = 9716487 | pmc = 1219691 | doi = 10.1042/bj3340297 }}</ref>\n\nIL-6 is probably the best-studied of the cytokines that use [[gp130]], also known as IL-6 signal transducer (IL6ST),  in their signalling complexes. Other cytokines that signal through receptors containing gp130 are [[Interleukin 11]] (IL-11), [[Interleukin 27]] (IL-27), [[ciliary neurotrophic factor]] (CNTF), [[cardiotrophin-1]] (CT-1), [[CLCF1|cardiotrophin-like cytokine]] (CLC), [[leukemia inhibitory factor]] (LIF), [[oncostatin M]] (OSM), [[Kaposi's sarcoma-associated herpesvirus]] interleukin 6-like protein ([[KSHV-IL6]]).<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Kishimoto T, Akira S, Narazaki M, Taga T | title = Interleukin-6 family of cytokines and gp130 | journal = Blood | volume = 86 | issue = 4 | pages = 1243\u201354 | date = August 1995 | pmid = 7632928 | doi = 10.1182/blood.V86.4.1243.bloodjournal8641243 }}</ref> These cytokines are commonly referred to as the ''IL-6 like'' or ''gp130 utilising'' cytokines <ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Heinrich PC, Behrmann I, Haan S, Hermanns HM, M\u00fcller-Newen G, Schaper F | title = Principles of interleukin (IL)-6-type cytokine signalling and its regulation | journal = The Biochemical Journal | volume = 374 | issue = Pt 1 | pages = 1\u201320 | date = August 2003 | pmid = 12773095 | pmc = 1223585 | doi = 10.1042/BJ20030407 }}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the membrane-bound receptor, a soluble form of IL-6R (sIL-6R) has been purified from human serum and urine. Many neuronal cells are unresponsive to stimulation by IL-6 alone, but differentiation and survival of neuronal cells can be mediated through the action of sIL-6R. The sIL-6R/IL-6 complex can stimulate neurites outgrowth and promote survival of neurons and, hence, may be important in nerve regeneration through remyelination.\n\n==  Interactions ==\n\nInterleukin-6 has been shown to [[Protein-protein interaction|interact]] with [[interleukin-6 receptor]],<ref name=\"pmid14557255\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Schwantner A, Dingley AJ, Ozbek S, Rose-John S, Gr\u00f6tzinger J | title = Direct determination of the interleukin-6 binding epitope of the interleukin-6 receptor by NMR spectroscopy | journal = The Journal of Biological Chemistry | volume = 279 | issue = 1 | pages = 571\u20136 | date = January 2004 | pmid = 14557255 | doi = 10.1074/jbc.M311019200 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid12643274\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Schuster B, Kovaleva M, Sun Y, Regenhard P, Matthews V, Gr\u00f6tzinger J, Rose-John S, Kallen KJ | display-authors = 6 | title = Signaling of human ciliary neurotrophic factor (CNTF) revisited. The interleukin-6 receptor can serve as an alpha-receptor for CTNF | journal = The Journal of Biological Chemistry | volume = 278 | issue = 11 | pages = 9528\u201335 | date = March 2003 | pmid = 12643274 | doi = 10.1074/jbc.M210044200 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid2788034\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Taga T, Hibi M, Hirata Y, Yamasaki K, Yasukawa K, Matsuda T, Hirano T, Kishimoto T | display-authors = 6 | title = Interleukin-6 triggers the association of its receptor with a possible signal transducer, gp130 | journal = Cell | volume = 58 | issue = 3 | pages = 573\u201381 | date = August 1989 | pmid = 2788034 | doi = 10.1016/0092-8674(89)90438-8 }}</ref> [[glycoprotein 130]],<ref name=\"pmid15989626\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Kallen KJ, zum B\u00fcschenfelde KH, Rose-John S | title = The therapeutic potential of interleukin-6 hyperagonists and antagonists | journal = Expert Opinion on Investigational Drugs | volume = 6 | issue = 3 | pages = 237\u201366 | date = March 1997 | pmid = 15989626 | doi = 10.1517/13543784.6.3.237 }}</ref> and [[Galectin-3]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Gordon-Alonso M, Bruger AM, van der Bruggen P | title = Extracellular galectins as controllers of cytokines in hematological cancer | journal = Blood | volume = 132 | issue = 5 | pages = 484\u2013491 | date = August 2018 | pmid = 29875102 | pmc = 6073326 | doi = 10.1182/blood-2018-04-846014 }}</ref>\n\nThere is considerable functional overlap and interaction between Substance P (SP), the natural ligand for the neurokinin type 1 receptor (NK1R, a mediator of immunomodulatory activity) and IL-6.\n\n== Role in disease ==\n\nIL-6 stimulates the inflammatory and auto-immune processes in many diseases such as [[diabetes]],<ref name=\"pmid16306329\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Kristiansen OP, Mandrup-Poulsen T | title = Interleukin-6 and diabetes: the good, the bad, or the indifferent? | journal = Diabetes | volume = 54 Suppl 2 | issue =  | pages = S114-24 | date = December 2005 | pmid = 16306329 | doi = 10.2337/diabetes.54.suppl_2.S114 }}</ref> [[atherosclerosis]],<ref name=\"pmid17684929\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Dubi\u0144ski A, Zdrojewicz Z | title = [The role of interleukin-6 in development and progression of atherosclerosis] | language = Polish | journal = Polski Merkuriusz Lekarski | volume = 22 | issue = 130 | pages = 291\u20134 | date = April 2007 | pmid = 17684929 | doi =  }}</ref> [[Major depressive disorder|depression]],<ref name=\"pmid 20015486\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Dowlati Y, Herrmann N, Swardfager W, Liu H, Sham L, Reim EK, Lanct\u00f4t KL | title = A meta-analysis of cytokines in major depression | journal = Biological Psychiatry | volume = 67 | issue = 5 | pages = 446\u201357 | date = March 2010 | pmid = 20015486 | doi = 10.1016/j.biopsych.2009.09.033 }}</ref> [[Alzheimer's Disease]],<ref name=\"pmid 20692646\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Swardfager W, Lanct\u00f4t K, Rothenburg L, Wong A, Cappell J, Herrmann N | title = A meta-analysis of cytokines in Alzheimer's disease | journal = Biological Psychiatry | volume = 68 | issue = 10 | pages = 930\u201341 | date = November 2010 | pmid = 20692646 | doi = 10.1016/j.biopsych.2010.06.012 }}</ref> [[systemic lupus erythematosus]],<ref name=\"pmid15230289\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Tackey E, Lipsky PE, Illei GG | title = Rationale for interleukin-6 blockade in systemic lupus erythematosus | journal = Lupus | volume = 13 | issue = 5 | pages = 339\u201343 | year = 2004 | pmid = 15230289 | pmc = 2014821 | doi = 10.1191/0961203304lu1023oa }}</ref> [[multiple myeloma]],<ref name=\"pmid10816321\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Gad\u00f3 K, Domj\u00e1n G, Hegyesi H, Falus A | title = Role of INTERLEUKIN-6 in the pathogenesis of multiple myeloma | journal = Cell Biology International | volume = 24 | issue = 4 | pages = 195\u2013209 | year = 2000 | pmid = 10816321 | doi = 10.1006/cbir.2000.0497 }}</ref> [[prostate cancer]],<ref name=\"pmid11312117\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Smith PC, Hobisch A, Lin DL, Culig Z, Keller ET | title = Interleukin-6 and prostate cancer progression | journal = Cytokine & Growth Factor Reviews | volume = 12 | issue = 1 | pages = 33\u201340 | date = March 2001 | pmid = 11312117 | doi = 10.1016/S1359-6101(00)00021-6 }}</ref> [[Beh\u00e7et's disease]],<ref name=\"pmid23257520\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hirohata S, Kikuchi H | title = Changes in biomarkers focused on differences in disease course or treatment in patients with neuro-Beh\u00e7et's disease | journal = Internal Medicine | volume = 51 | issue = 24 | pages = 3359\u201365 | date = Dec 2012 | pmid = 23257520 | doi = 10.2169/internalmedicine.51.8583 }}</ref> and [[rheumatoid arthritis]].<ref name=\"pmid16582692\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Nishimoto N | title = Interleukin-6 in rheumatoid arthritis | journal = Current Opinion in Rheumatology | volume = 18 | issue = 3 | pages = 277\u201381 | date = May 2006 | pmid = 16582692 | doi = 10.1097/01.bor.0000218949.19860.d1 }}</ref>\n\nHence, there is an interest in developing [[anti-IL-6]] agents as therapy against many of these diseases.<ref name=\"pmid16083340\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Barton BE | title = Interleukin-6 and new strategies for the treatment of cancer, hyperproliferative diseases and paraneoplastic syndromes | journal = Expert Opinion on Therapeutic Targets | volume = 9 | issue = 4 | pages = 737\u201352 | date = August 2005 | pmid = 16083340 | doi = 10.1517/14728222.9.4.737 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid16899109\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Smolen JS, Maini RN | title = Interleukin-6: a new therapeutic target | journal = Arthritis Research & Therapy | volume = 8 Suppl 2 | issue = Suppl 2 | pages = S5 | year = 2006 | pmid = 16899109 | pmc = 3226077 | doi = 10.1186/ar1969 }}</ref> The first such is [[tocilizumab]], which has been approved for [[rheumatoid arthritis]],<ref name=\"EmeryKeystone2008\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Emery P, Keystone E, Tony HP, Cantagrel A, van Vollenhoven R, Sanchez A, Alecock E, Lee J, Kremer J | display-authors = 6 | title = IL-6 receptor inhibition with tocilizumab improves treatment outcomes in patients with rheumatoid arthritis refractory to anti-tumour necrosis factor biologicals: results from a 24-week multicentre randomised placebo-controlled trial | journal = Annals of the Rheumatic Diseases | volume = 67 | issue = 11 | pages = 1516\u201323 | date = November 2008 | pmid = 18625622 | pmc = 3811149 | doi = 10.1136/ard.2008.092932 }}</ref> [[Castleman's disease]]<ref name=\"Nishimoto2005\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Nishimoto N, Kanakura Y, Aozasa K, Johkoh T, Nakamura M, Nakano S, Nakano N, Ikeda Y, Sasaki T, Nishioka K, Hara M, Taguchi H, Kimura Y, Kato Y, Asaoku H, Kumagai S, Kodama F, Nakahara H, Hagihara K, Yoshizaki K, Kishimoto T | display-authors = 6 | title = Humanized anti-interleukin-6 receptor antibody treatment of multicentric Castleman disease | journal = Blood | volume = 106 | issue = 8 | pages = 2627\u201332 | date = October 2005 | pmid = 15998837 | doi = 10.1182/blood-2004-12-4602 }}</ref> and [[systemic juvenile idiopathic arthritis]].<ref name=\"YokotaImagawa2008\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Yokota S, Imagawa T, Mori M, Miyamae T, Aihara Y, Takei S, Iwata N, Umebayashi H, Murata T, Miyoshi M, Tomiita M, Nishimoto N, Kishimoto T | display-authors = 6 | title = Efficacy and safety of tocilizumab in patients with systemic-onset juvenile idiopathic arthritis: a randomised, double-blind, placebo-controlled, withdrawal phase III trial | journal = Lancet | volume = 371 | issue = 9617 | pages = 998\u20131006 | date = March 2008 | pmid = 18358927 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(08)60454-7 }}</ref>  Others are in clinical trials.<ref name=N-2013>[http://www.nature.com/nm/journal/v19/n10/full/nm1013-1193.html First IL-6\u2013blocking drug nears approval for rare blood disorder], Nature Medicine, October 7, 2013</ref>\n\n===Rheumatoid arthritis===\nThe first FDA approved [[anti-IL-6]] treatment was for rheumatoid arthritis.\n\n=== Cancer ===\n[[Anti-IL-6]] therapy was initially developed for treatment of [[autoimmune diseases]], but due to the role of IL-6 in chronic inflammation, IL-6 blockade was also evaluated for cancer treatment.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Korneev KV, Atretkhany KN, Drutskaya MS, Grivennikov SI, Kuprash DV, Nedospasov SA | title = TLR-signaling and proinflammatory cytokines as drivers of tumorigenesis | journal = Cytokine | volume = 89 | pages = 127\u2013135 | date = January 2017 | pmid = 26854213 | doi = 10.1016/j.cyto.2016.01.021 }}</ref><ref name=\"AnestakisPetanidis2015\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Anestakis D, Petanidis S, Kalyvas S, Nday CM, Tsave O, Kioseoglou E, Salifoglou A | title = Mechanisms and applications of interleukins in cancer immunotherapy | journal = International Journal of Molecular Sciences | volume = 16 | issue = 1 | pages = 1691\u2013710 | date = January 2015 | pmid = 25590298 | pmc = 4307328 | doi = 10.3390/ijms16011691 }}</ref> IL-6 was seen to have roles in tumor microenvironment regulation,<ref name=\"LiMo2012\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Li J, Mo HY, Xiong G, Zhang L, He J, Huang ZF, Liu ZW, Chen QY, Du ZM, Zheng LM, Qian CN, Zeng YX | display-authors = 6 | title = Tumor microenvironment macrophage inhibitory factor directs the accumulation of interleukin-17-producing tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes and predicts favorable survival in nasopharyngeal carcinoma patients | journal = The Journal of Biological Chemistry | volume = 287 | issue = 42 | pages = 35484\u201395 | date = October 2012 | pmid = 22893706 | pmc = 3471767 | doi = 10.1074/jbc.M112.367532 }}</ref> production of [[breast cancer]] stem cell-like cells,<ref name=\"Yuan2011\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Xie G, Yao Q, Liu Y, Du S, Liu A, Guo Z, Sun A, Ruan J, Chen L, Ye C, Yuan Y | display-authors = 6 | title = IL-6-induced epithelial-mesenchymal transition promotes the generation of breast cancer stem-like cells analogous to mammosphere cultures | journal = International Journal of Oncology | volume = 40 | issue = 4 | pages = 1171\u20139 | date = April 2012 | pmid = 22134360 | pmc = 3584811 | doi = 10.3892/ijo.2011.1275 }}</ref> metastasis through down-regulation of E-cadherin,<ref name=\"MiaoLiu2014\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Miao JW, Liu LJ, Huang J | title = Interleukin-6-induced epithelial-mesenchymal transition through signal transducer and activator of transcription 3 in human cervical carcinoma | journal = International Journal of Oncology | volume = 45 | issue = 1 | pages = 165\u201376 | date = July 2014 | pmid = 24806843 | doi = 10.3892/ijo.2014.2422 }}</ref> and alteration of DNA methylation in oral cancer.<ref name=\"GascheHoffmann2011\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Gasche JA, Hoffmann J, Boland CR, Goel A | title = Interleukin-6 promotes tumorigenesis by altering DNA methylation in oral cancer cells | journal = International Journal of Cancer | volume = 129 | issue = 5 | pages = 1053\u201363 | date = September 2011 | pmid = 21710491 | pmc = 3110561 | doi = 10.1002/ijc.25764 }}</ref>\n\nAdvanced/[[metastatic cancer]] patients have higher levels of IL-6 in their blood.<ref name=\"urlMedscape.com Log In\">{{cite web | url = http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/537309 | title =  Cancer Patients Typically Have Increased Interleukin-6 Levels | date = 2006-06-26 | format = | work = American Society of Clinical Oncology 2006 Annual Meeting, Abstracts 8632 and 8633 | publisher = Medscape.com }}</ref> One example of this is [[pancreatic cancer]], with noted elevation of IL-6 present in patients correlating with poor survival rates.<ref name=\"BelloneSmirne2005\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Bellone G, Smirne C, Mauri FA, Tonel E, Carbone A, Buffolino A, Dughera L, Robecchi A, Pirisi M, Emanuelli G | display-authors = 6 | title = Cytokine expression profile in human pancreatic carcinoma cells and in surgical specimens: implications for survival | journal = Cancer Immunology, Immunotherapy | volume = 55 | issue = 6 | pages = 684\u201398 | date = June 2006 | pmid = 16094523 | doi = 10.1007/s00262-005-0047-0 }}</ref>\n\n=== Infectious diseases ===\n\n====Enterovirus 71====\nHigh IL-6 levels are associated with the development of [[encephalitis]] in children and immunodeficient [[Laboratory mouse|mouse models]] infected with [[Enterovirus 71]]; this highly contagious virus normally causes a milder illness called [[Hand, foot, and mouth disease]] but can cause life-threatening encephalitis in some cases. EV71 patients with a certain [[gene polymorphism]] in IL-6 also appear to be more susceptible to developing encephalitis.\n\n=== Epigenetic modifications  ===\n\nIL-6 has been shown to lead to several neurological diseases through its impact on [[epigenetics|epigenetic]] modification within the brain.<ref name=\"pmid17913903\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Smith SE, Li J, Garbett K, Mirnics K, Patterson PH | title = Maternal immune activation alters fetal brain development through interleukin-6 | journal = The Journal of Neuroscience | volume = 27 | issue = 40 | pages = 10695\u2013702 | date = October 2007 | pmid = 17913903 | pmc = 2387067 | doi = 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.2178-07.2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid19029285\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Kundakovic M, Chen Y, Guidotti A, Grayson DR | title = The reelin and GAD67 promoters are activated by epigenetic drugs that facilitate the disruption of local repressor complexes | journal = Molecular Pharmacology | volume = 75 | issue = 2 | pages = 342\u201354 | date = February 2009 | pmid = 19029285 | pmc = 2684898 | doi = 10.1124/mol.108.051763 }}</ref> IL-6 activates the [[Phosphoinositide 3-kinase]] (PI3K) pathway, and a downstream target of this pathway is the [[AKT|protein kinase B]] (PKB) (Hodge et al., 2007). IL-6 activated PKB can phosphorylate the nuclear localization signal on [[DNMT1|DNA methyltransferase-1]] (DNMT1).<ref name=\"pmid18204201\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hodge DR, Cho E, Copeland TD, Guszczynski T, Yang E, Seth AK, Farrar WL | title = IL-6 enhances the nuclear translocation of DNA cytosine-5-methyltransferase 1 (DNMT1) via phosphorylation of the nuclear localization sequence by the AKT kinase | journal = Cancer Genomics & Proteomics | volume = 4 | issue = 6 | pages = 387\u201398 | year = 2007 | pmid = 18204201 | doi =  }}</ref> This phosphorylation causes movement of DNMT1 to the nucleus, where it can be transcribed.<ref name=\"pmid18204201\"/> DNMT1 recruits other DNMTs, including DNMT3A and DNMT3B, which, as a complex, recruit [[HDAC1]].<ref name=\"pmid19029285\"/> This complex adds methyl groups to [[CpG islands]] on gene promoters, repressing the chromatin structure surrounding the DNA sequence and inhibiting transcriptional machinery from accessing the gene to induce transcription.<ref name=\"pmid19029285\"/> Increased IL-6, therefore, can hypermethylate DNA sequences and subsequently decrease gene expression through its effects on DNMT1 expression.<ref name=\"pmid20354000\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Foran E, Garrity-Park MM, Mureau C, Newell J, Smyrk TC, Limburg PJ, Egan LJ | title = Upregulation of DNA methyltransferase-mediated gene silencing, anchorage-independent growth, and migration of colon cancer cells by interleukin-6 | journal = Molecular Cancer Research | volume = 8 | issue = 4 | pages = 471\u201381 | date = April 2010 | pmid = 20354000 | doi = 10.1158/1541-7786.MCR-09-0496 }}</ref>\n\n==== Schizophrenia ====\n\nThe induction of epigenetic modification by IL-6 has been proposed as a mechanism in the pathology of schizophrenia through the hypermethylation and repression of the [[Glutamate decarboxylase|GAD67]] promoter.<ref name=\"pmid19029285\"/> This hypermethylation may potentially lead to the decreased GAD67 levels seen in the brains of people with schizophrenia.<ref name=\"pmid11074872\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Guidotti A, Auta J, Davis JM, Di-Giorgi-Gerevini V, Dwivedi Y, Grayson DR, Impagnatiello F, Pandey G, Pesold C, Sharma R, Uzunov D, Costa E, DiGiorgi Gerevini V | display-authors = 6 | title = Decrease in reelin and glutamic acid decarboxylase67 (GAD67) expression in schizophrenia and bipolar disorder: a postmortem brain study | journal = Archives of General Psychiatry | volume = 57 | issue = 11 | pages = 1061\u20139 | date = November 2000 | pmid = 11074872 | doi = 10.1001/archpsyc.57.11.1061 }}</ref> GAD67 may be involved in the pathology of schizophrenia through its effect on [[gamma-Aminobutyric acid|GABA]] levels and on [[neural oscillation]]s.<ref name=\"pmid22806213\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Gandal MJ, Sisti J, Klook K, Ortinski PI, Leitman V, Liang Y, Thieu T, Anderson R, Pierce RC, Jonak G, Gur RE, Carlson G, Siegel SJ | display-authors = 6 | title = GABAB-mediated rescue of altered excitatory-inhibitory balance, gamma synchrony and behavioral deficits following constitutive NMDAR-hypofunction | journal = Translational Psychiatry | volume = 2 | issue = 7 | pages = e142 | date = July 2012 | pmid = 22806213 | pmc = 3410621 | doi = 10.1038/tp.2012.69 }}</ref> Neural oscillations occur when inhibitory GABAergic neurons fire synchronously and cause inhibition of a multitude of target excitatory neurons at the same time, leading to a cycle of inhibition and disinhibition.<ref name=\"pmid22806213\"/> These neural oscillations are impaired in schizophrenia, and these alterations may be responsible for both positive and negative symptoms of schizophrenia.<ref name=\"pmid20087360\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Uhlhaas PJ, Singer W | title = Abnormal neural oscillations and synchrony in schizophrenia | journal = Nature Reviews. Neuroscience | volume = 11 | issue = 2 | pages = 100\u201313 | date = February 2010 | pmid = 20087360 | doi = 10.1038/nrn2774 }}</ref>\n\n==== Depression and major depressive disorder ====\n{{See also|Epigenetics of depression#Brain-derived neurotrophic factor, Epigenetics of schizophrenia#Methylation of BDNF}}\nThe epigenetic effects IL-6 have also been implicated in the pathology of [[Depression (mood)|depression]]. The effects of IL-6 on depression are mediated through the repression of [[brain-derived neurotrophic factor]] (BDNF) expression in the brain; DNMT1 hypermethylates the BDNF promoter and reduces BDNF levels.<ref name=\"pmid18536530\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Sharma RP, Tun N, Grayson DR | title = Depolarization induces downregulation of DNMT1 and DNMT3a in primary cortical cultures | journal = Epigenetics | volume = 3 | issue = 2 | pages = 74\u201380 | year = 2008 | pmid = 18536530 | doi = 10.4161/epi.3.2.6103 }}</ref> Altered BDNF function has been implicated in depression,<ref name=\"pmid16343697\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hwang JP, Tsai SJ, Hong CJ, Yang CH, Lirng JF, Yang YM | title = The Val66Met polymorphism of the brain-derived neurotrophic-factor gene is associated with geriatric depression | journal = Neurobiology of Aging | volume = 27 | issue = 12 | pages = 1834\u20137 | date = December 2006 | pmid = 16343697 | doi = 10.1016/j.neurobiolaging.2005.10.013 }}</ref> which is likely due to epigenetic modification following IL-6 upregulation.<ref name=\"pmid18536530\"/> BDNF is a neutrophic factor implicated in spine formation, density, and morphology on neurons.<ref name=\"pmid15882774\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Ethell IM, Pasquale EB | title = Molecular mechanisms of dendritic spine development and remodeling | journal = Progress in Neurobiology | volume = 75 | issue = 3 | pages = 161\u2013205 | date = February 2005 | pmid = 15882774 | doi = 10.1016/j.pneurobio.2005.02.003 }}</ref> Downregulation of BDNF, therefore, may cause decreased connectivity in the brain. Depression is marked by altered connectivity, in particular between the [[anterior cingulate cortex]] and several other limbic areas, such as the [[hippocampus]].<ref name=\"pmid17210143\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Greicius MD, Flores BH, Menon V, Glover GH, Solvason HB, Kenna H, Reiss AL, Schatzberg AF | display-authors = 6 | title = Resting-state functional connectivity in major depression: abnormally increased contributions from subgenual cingulate cortex and thalamus | journal = Biological Psychiatry | volume = 62 | issue = 5 | pages = 429\u201337 | date = September 2007 | pmid = 17210143 | pmc = 2001244 | doi = 10.1016/j.biopsych.2006.09.020 }}</ref> The anterior cingulate cortex is responsible for detecting incongruences between expectation and perceived experience.<ref name=\"pmid16819523\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Somerville LH, Heatherton TF, Kelley WM | title = Anterior cingulate cortex responds differentially to expectancy violation and social rejection | journal = Nature Neuroscience | volume = 9 | issue = 8 | pages = 1007\u20138 | date = August 2006 | pmid = 16819523 | doi = 10.1038/nn1728 }}</ref> Altered connectivity of the anterior cingulate cortex in depression, therefore, may cause altered emotions following certain experiences, leading to depressive reactions.<ref name=\"pmid16819523\"/> This altered connectivity is mediated by IL-6 and its effect on epigenetic regulation of BDNF.<ref name=\"pmid18536530\"/>\n\nAdditional preclinical and clinical data, suggest that [[Substance P]] [SP] and IL-6 may act in concert to promote major depression. SP, a hybrid neurotransmitter-cytokine, is co-transmitted with BDNF through paleo-spinothalamic circuitry from the periphery with collaterals into key areas of the limbic system. However, both IL6 and SP mitigate expression of BDNF in brain regions associated with negative affect and memory. SP and IL6 both relax tight junctions of the blood brain barrier, such that effects seen in fMRI experiments with these molecules may be a bidirectional mix of neuronal, glial, capillary, synaptic, paracrine, or endocrine-like effects. At the cellular level, SP is noted to increase expression of interleukin-6 (IL-6) through PI-3K, p42/44 and p38 MAP kinase pathways. Data suggest that nuclear translocation of NF-\u03baB regulates IL-6 overexpression in SP-stimulated cells.<ref name=\"pmid14654230\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Azzolina A, Bongiovanni A, Lampiasi N | title = Substance P induces TNF-alpha and IL-6 production through NF kappa B in peritoneal mast cells | journal = Biochimica et Biophysica Acta | volume = 1643 | issue = 1\u20133 | pages = 75\u201383 | date = December 2003 | pmid = 14654230 | doi = 10.1016/j.bbamcr.2003.09.003 }}</ref> This is of key interest as: 1) a meta-analysis indicates an association of major depressive disorder, C-reactive protein and IL6 plasma concentrations,<ref name=\"pmid26065825\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Haapakoski R, Mathieu J, Ebmeier KP, Alenius H, Kivim\u00e4ki M | title = Cumulative meta-analysis of interleukins 6 and 1\u03b2, tumour necrosis factor \u03b1 and C-reactive protein in patients with major depressive disorder | journal = Brain, Behavior, and Immunity | volume = 49 | issue =  | pages = 206\u201315 | date = October 2015 | pmid = 26065825 | pmc = 4566946 | doi = 10.1016/j.bbi.2015.06.001 }}</ref> 2) NK1R antagonists [five molecules] studied by 3 independent groups in over 2000 patients from 1998-2013 validate the mechanism as dose-related, fully effective antidepressant,  with a unique safety profile.<ref name=\"pmid23539641\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Ratti E, Bettica P, Alexander R, Archer G, Carpenter D, Evoniuk G, Gomeni R, Lawson E, Lopez M, Millns H, Rabiner EA, Trist D, Trower M, Zamuner S, Krishnan R, Fava M | display-authors = 6 | title = Full central neurokinin-1 receptor blockade is required for efficacy in depression: evidence from orvepitant clinical studies | journal = Journal of Psychopharmacology | volume = 27 | issue = 5 | pages = 424\u201334 | date = May 2013 | pmid = 23539641 | doi = 10.1177/0269881113480990 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid9733503\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Kramer MS, Cutler N, Feighner J, Shrivastava R, Carman J, Sramek JJ, Reines SA, Liu G, Snavely D, Wyatt-Knowles E, Hale JJ, Mills SG, MacCoss M, Swain CJ, Harrison T, Hill RG, Hefti F, Scolnick EM, Cascieri MA, Chicchi GG, Sadowski S, Williams AR, Hewson L, Smith D, Carlson EJ, Hargreaves RJ, Rupniak NM | display-authors = 6 | title = Distinct mechanism for antidepressant activity by blockade of central substance P receptors | journal = Science | volume = 281 | issue = 5383 | pages = 1640\u20135 | date = September 1998 | pmid = 9733503 | doi = 10.1126/science.281.5383.1640 | bibcode = 1998Sci...281.1640K }}</ref> [[Aprepitant#Major Depression|(see Summary of NK1RAs in Major Depression)]], 3) the preliminary observation that plasma concentrations of IL6 are elevated in depressed patients with cancer,<ref name=\"pmid11481159\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Musselman DL, Miller AH, Porter MR, Manatunga A, Gao F, Penna S, Pearce BD, Landry J, Glover S, McDaniel JS, Nemeroff CB | display-authors = 6 | title = Higher than normal plasma interleukin-6 concentrations in cancer patients with depression: preliminary findings | journal = The American Journal of Psychiatry | volume = 158 | issue = 8 | pages = 1252\u20137 | date = August 2001 | pmid = 11481159 | doi = 10.1176/appi.ajp.158.8.1252 }}</ref> and 4) selective NK1RAs may eliminate endogenous SP stress-induced augmentation of IL-6 secretion pre-clinically.<ref name=\"pmid8642417\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Zhu GF, Chancellor-Freeland C, Berman AS, Kage R, Leeman SE, Beller DI, Black PH | title = Endogenous substance P mediates cold water stress-induced increase in interleukin-6 secretion from peritoneal macrophages | journal = The Journal of Neuroscience | volume = 16 | issue = 11 | pages = 3745\u201352 | date = June 1996 | pmid = 8642417 | pmc = 6578844 | doi = 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.16-11-03745.1996 }}</ref> These and many other reports suggest that a clinical study of a neutralizing IL-6 biological or drug based antagonist is likely warranted in patients with major depressive disorder, with or without co-morbid chronic inflammatory based illnesses; that the combination of NK1RAs and IL6 blockers may represent a new, potentially biomarkable approach to major depression, and possibly [[bipolar disorder]].\n\nThe IL-6 antibody [[sirukumab]] is now undergoing clinical trials against [[major depressive disorder]].<ref>{{ClinicalTrialsGov|NCT02473289|An Efficacy and Safety Study of Sirukumab in Participants With Major Depressive Disorder.}}</ref>\n\n===Asthma===\nObesity is a known risk factor in the development of severe asthma. Recent data suggests that the inflammation associated with obesity, potentially mediated by the cytokine IL6, plays a role in causing poor lung function and increased risk for developing asthma exacerbations.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Peters MC, McGrath KW, Hawkins GA, Hastie AT, Levy BD, Israel E, Phillips BR, Mauger DT, Comhair SA, Erzurum SC, Johansson MW, Jarjour NN, Coverstone AM, Castro M, Holguin F, Wenzel SE, Woodruff PG, Bleecker ER, Fahy JV | display-authors = 6 | title = Plasma interleukin-6 concentrations, metabolic dysfunction, and asthma severity: a cross-sectional analysis of two cohorts | journal = The Lancet. Respiratory Medicine | volume = 4 | issue = 7 | pages = 574\u2013584 | date = July 2016 | pmid = 27283230 | pmc = 5007068 | doi = 10.1016/S2213-2600(16)30048-0 }}</ref>\n\n== Protein superfamily ==\nInterleukin is the main member of the IL-6 superfamily ({{Pfam|PF00489}}), which also includes [[Granulocyte colony-stimulating factor|G-CSF]], [[Interleukin-23|IL23A]], and CLCF1. A viral version of IL6 is found in [[Kaposi's sarcoma-associated herpesvirus]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Suthaus J, Stuhlmann-Laeisz C, Tompkins VS, Rosean TR, Klapper W, Tosato G, Janz S, Scheller J, Rose-John S | display-authors = 6 | title = HHV-8-encoded viral IL-6 collaborates with mouse IL-6 in the development of multicentric Castleman disease in mice | journal = Blood | volume = 119 | issue = 22 | pages = 5173\u201381 | date = May 2012 | pmid = 22490805 | doi = 10.1182/blood-2011-09-377705 | pmc = 3370672 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.cancerindex.org/geneweb/IL6.htm IL-6 expression in various cancers]\n\n{{PDB Gallery|geneid=3569}}\n{{Interleukins}}\n{{Neurotrophic factors}}\n{{Interleukin receptor modulators}}\n\n[[Category:Interleukins]]\n[[Category:Osaka University research]]\n[[Category:Neurotrophic factors]]\n", "name_user": "Hqb", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFunction:fix broken/dead doi", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interleukin_6"}
{"title_page": "New Democracy (Greece)", "text_new": "{{short description|Greek political party}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = New Democracy\n| logo = File:New Democracy Logo 2018.png\n| colorcode = {{New Democracy (Greece)/meta/color}}\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|1974|10|4|df=y}}\n| international = [[Centrist Democrat International]]<br>[[International Democrat Union]]\n| website = {{official URL}}\n| country = Greece\n| native_name = \u039d\u03ad\u03b1 \u0394\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03ba\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03af\u03b1<br>''Nea Dimokratia''\n| abbreviation = ND (\u039d\u0394)\n| leader1_title = President\n| leader1_name = [[Kyriakos Mitsotakis]]\n| leader2_title = Vice Presidents\n| leader2_name = [[Kostis Hatzidakis]]<ref name=\"VPs\">[http://www.tovima.gr/en/article/?aid=769707 \"Kostis Hatzidakis and Adonis Georgiadis appointed New Democracy VPs\"]. ''[[To Vima]]''. 18 January 2016.</ref><br>[[Adonis Georgiadis]]<ref name=\"VPs\"/>\n| leader3_title = Secretary\n| leader3_name = Lefteris Avgenakis\n| leader4_title = Spokesperson\n| leader4_name = Sofia Zacharaki\n| leader5_title = Founder\n| leader5_name = [[Konstantinos Karamanlis]]\n| predecessor = [[National Radical Union]]\n| youth_wing = [[Youth Organisation of New Democracy]]\n| wing1_title = Foundation\n| wing1 = [[Constantinos Karamanlis Institute for Democracy]]\n| ideology = {{nowrap|[[Liberal conservatism]]<ref name=\"Magone2003\"/><ref name=\"Urwin2014\"/><ref name=Nordsieck/><br>[[Christian democracy]]<ref name=Nordsieck>{{cite web|url=http://parties-and-elections.eu/greece.html|title=Greece|last=Nordsieck|first=Wolfram|date=2015|website=Parties and Elections in Europe}}</ref><ref name=\"Ezrow2011\">{{cite book|author=Lawrence Ezrow|chapter=Electoral systems and party responsiveness|editor1=Norman Schofield|editor2=Gonzalo Caballero|title=Political Economy of Institutions, Democracy and Voting|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-wthzLK6m8gC&pg=PA320|